<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
--Boris Yeltsin defeated Gennady Zyuganov by a surprisingly
wide margin in Russian presidential election but his health
problem looms for his second term.
</P>
<P>
--Across the country, Americans will celebrate U.S. Independence
Day today in varied fashions.
</P>
<P>
--A regional proposal to send foreign troops into Burundi to
stop an intensifying ethnic war between the Hudu and Tutsi is
gathering the momentum.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
--At the very moment when Republicans see a new vulnerability
in President Clinton, Robert Dole has reinforced the concerns about
his campaigning ability by lashing out at a TV network tobacco man
over the tobacco issue.
</P>
<P>
--Unusual heat damages were founded in the boosters used to
launch the space shuttle Columbia scheduled on July 20 and it
could force NASA to delay the flight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
