<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agrotechnique Helps Feed 64 Million Poor Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 64.6 million people in
China's poor rural areas are no longer threatened by hunger,
thanks to a state-sponsored agricultural technique promotion
project that has been in use for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The technique, which boosts maize yield by using hybrid seeds
and plastic sheets, was used on 3.626 million hectares of farmland
in poor regions in 16 provinces including Sichuan, Hubei, Yunnan,
Gansu, Guizhou and Shaanxi -- 54 percent more than the planned
figure.
</P>
<P>
Each hectare of farmland that uses the seed/plastic method can
harvest 2,505 kg more maize, enough to feed an additional 15
people.
</P>
<P>
Working jointly to promote the technique are the State Planning
Commission, the Ministry of Agriculture, Ministry of Finance,
China Agricultural Technology Promotion Center, and the Leading
Group for Economic Development of impoverished Areas under the
State Council.
</P>
<P>
China has 65 million people who still live below the poverty
level. They mainly inhabit the mountain or plateau areas in the
west and central regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the China Agricultural Technology Promotion
Center said that popularizing this technique is one important way
for these people to overcome poverty during the Ninth Five-Year
Plan period (1996-2000). 
</P>
</TEXT>
