<HEADLINE> Germany Provides Namibia With Development Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Germany is providing 40
million Deutsche Marks (about 26.6 million US Dollars) in
development aid to Namibia in 1996, the South African Press
Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Windhoek, the German embassy said
more than half of the money would be used for financial
cooperation projects, including Windhoek's water reclamation
system to "defeat the water crisis in the capital".
</P>
<P>
Funds had also been made available for an environmental impact
study on the extraction of water from the Okavango River for use
in central Namibia, and improving primary school infrastructures,
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The aid agreement was signed on Wednesday by Rainer Barthelt,
Director-general for sub-Saharan Africa in the German Ministry of
Cooperation and Development, and Director-general of Namibian
National Planning Commission Saara Kuugongelwa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
