<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Severe Floods Hit Zhejiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Three days of torrential rain has
caused severe flooding in east China's Zhejiang Province,
destroying more than 50,000 houses and inundating 130,000 hectares
of farmland.
</P>
<P>
The heavy rains started early on June 30 and continued until
the evening of July 3, pouring down 300 millimeters of rain on
5,000 square kilometers of land in northern Zhejiang, official
sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The rains have boosted the local rivers and reservoirs to
record-high levels, and caused floods that have victimized 1.2
million people.
</P>
<P>
People's Liberation Army soldiers and armed policemen have been
sent to the flood-stricken areas to aid in rescues, and to bring
fresh water, food and medicine to the flood victims.
</P>
<P>
So far, traffic and telecommunications services have resumed in
most of the flooded areas. People besieged by the floods have been
evacuated, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains are expected to continue for the next two days in
the flooded area, according to weather forecast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
