<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-04 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Orders Release of Jailed Islamic Activists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat today ordered the release of
hundreds of Hamas and Islamic Jihad activists jailed in the
self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said that the release of the activists was conducted
"on condition that Palestinian security is not harmed."
</P>
<P>
Over 700 Islamic militant activists have been jailed by the
PNA security forces in a widespread crackdown launched after a
spate of terrorist suicide bombings killed 58 people inside
Israel from late February to early March.
</P>
<P>
The Hamas and Islamic Jihad, two leading Islamic militant
groups that oppose the Israeli-Palestinian peace process, claimed
responsibility for the suicide attacks.
</P>
<P>
Under Israel's pressure, Arafat ordered Palestinian security
forces to crack down the Islamic militant suspects by raiding
mosques, homes and Islamic institutions.
</P>
<P>
Hamas and Islamic Jihad strongly denounced the PNA's
crackdown, justifying their militant activities in Israel as a
form of resistance against Israeli occupation of Palestinian
lands.
</P>
<P>
Israel has imposed a crippling closure on the Palestinian
self-rule areas of the West Bank and Gaza Strip since the start of
the suicide attacks, inflicting severe hardship on the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Pressure on Arafat to release the jailed Islamic activists by
the Palestinian public has increased because of the continued
closure and the election victory by Israeli hardline Likud leader
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who promised to deliver secure peace to Israeli
people, has conditioned the progress of Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks on what he called PNA's fulfilment of its commitments to
fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Arafat today approved the family of
Yahya Ayyash, Hamas' chief bomb-maker killed by Israeli agents in
January, to rebuild its West Bank home which was destroyed by
Israeli security forces after the February terrorist attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
