<HEADLINE> S. African Minister Calls on Businessmen to Stop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Trade and Industry Minister
Alec Erwin today called on South African businessmen to stop
complaining and concentrate instead on the country's economic
prospects.
</P>
<P>
Addressing clothing and textile sector representatives at a
conference in Durban, Erwin said international traders remained
optimistic about South Africa's prospects, though this sentiment
was not always shared by their South African counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Erwin, who recently met European business leaders, said it was
time for South Africans to rise to the country's economic
challenges.
</P>
<P>
''In South Africa we have a tendency to whinge and talk some
blatant nonsense. To whinge earns you a disrespect,'' said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that foreign investors knew South Africa had
problems, but their view of the country's potential for success
was ''sometimes far better''.
</P>
<P>
Fundamental changes in international trade would necessitate a
more flexible and dynamic approach among South African business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
To this regard, Erwin said other countries' ability to rapidly
translate new technology into advanced production was possibly
the greatest challenge to ''protectionist'' attitudes in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
He further highlighted the need to play a constructive role in
developing the southern African region or risk ''harsh
consequences''.
</P>
<P>
''If South Africa plays a constructive role, we will get a
staggering good will and support from whithin the region, if not,
we will be treated very harshly,'' he added. enditem

