<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Launch More Than 10 Hughes Satellites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Japan and the Hughes Electronics
Corp. Group have agreed to launch more than 10 satellites next
century for the latter by using a remodeled version of Japan's
H-II rocket, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
A contract will be signed next month between Rocket Systems
Corp., a Japanese rocket consortium, and Hughes Space and
Communications International, a newspaper quoted Japanese space
industry sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The contract, the first for using a Japanese rocket to launch
foreign satellites, will also be the first foreign commercial
launching contract for the H-II rocket since it made its first
successful flight in February 1994.
</P>
<P>
The latest deal will signal Japan's entry into the fiercely
competitive business of commercial satellite launching, a market
where the U.S., European, Russian and Chinese companies vie with
each other for about 30 launches a year, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Rocket Systems will use a remodeled version of
the H-II, called the H-IIA, to launch more than 10 satellites
scheduled to be made by Hughes between 2000 and 2004.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese rocket consortium is involved with 73 local
aerospace firms, nonlife insurance companies and banks. The H-II
rocket is the first major launching platform developed entirely in
Japan and the only rocket in the country capable for launching a
2-ton satellite into stationary orbit. So far, three H-II rockets
have been successfully launched. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
