<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Britain's Opposition Unveils Blueprint To </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Opposition leader Tony
Blair today formally launched his bid for power at the next
election, saying he would create a "genuinely one-nation society"
with "new vision and new direction."
</P>
<P>
Unveiling his long-awaited "Road to the Manifesto" document --
Labor's election blueprint -- Blair told voters that they were
offered a choice between "hope and fear" at the next election.
</P>
<P>
The Labor government would give ordinary British people "a
square, fair deal" if they elected him prime minister, Blair said.
People would feel how everyday lives would be changed by Labor
without bringing higher tax bills, he added.
</P>
<P>
The manifesto's main pledges are:
</P>
<P>
-- Cutting National Health Service (NHS) waiting lists by
100,000 by releasing cash from the NHS red tape,
</P>
<P>
-- Slashing primary school classes to below 30 pupils,
</P>
<P>
-- A job creation scheme for the young unemployed funded by a
windfall tax,
</P>
<P>
-- Fast track punishment for persistent young offenders, and
</P>
<P>
-- Ensuring sound finances by holding down public spending.
</P>
<P>
The document also makes emphasis on defense and foreign
affairs, pledging to have strong defense and leadership for
Britain and retain the European Union (EU) veto on key issues, EU
reform and a more effective UN.
</P>
<P>
On Northern Ireland affairs, the manifesto said, Labor will
stick to the commitment to reconciliation between conflicted
communities and unity of Irish people.
</P>
<P>
It is believed today's 36-page guide document is the most
detailed program ever put out by an opposition party so far ahead
of an election.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Conservative Party attacked Labor's "Road to the
Manifesto" as "the road to ruin."
</P>
<P>
Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke said voters should
not believe Labor's economic pledges designed to remove its old
image as a high-tax, high-spending party.
</P>
<P>
"The unmistakable fact is that to deliver on any of these
promises, Labor would have to raise taxes, put up borrowing, or
do both," the finance minister said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Labor's manifesto, the Independent newspaper
wrote in its editorial entitled "Steady, Tony, it could still fall
apart:" "The Labor leader bears his policy document like an
anxious curator with a priceless vase. But on slippery ground, he
is right to be cautious." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
