<HEADLINE> President Places Hope on US Help for Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The people of Cyprus place their
hope in the United States for realizing the principles of freedom
and justice for their divided island, Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides said here today.
</P>
<P>
In a congratulatory message to President Bill Clinton on the
occasion of the anniversary of the U.S. Independence Day,
President Clerides noted that "the declaration of independence of
the U.S. marked a new beginning in world history signaling the
birth of freedom, justice and human rights throughout the
world."
</P>
<P>
He said that "two hundred and twenty years later all humanity
in its search for world peace is still guided by the spirit of
these principles."
</P>
<P>
"The people of Cyprus, who for 22 years are striving to
reunite their country, today place their hopes in the U.S.A. and
especially to your personal involvement for the realization of
the same principles which will culminate in a just settlement of
the Cyprus question based on the United Nations resolutions and
the principles of international law," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot president reiterated his government's readiness for
the further enhancement of the relations of friendship and
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
President Clerides paid an official visit to the United states
last month and held talks with Clinton at the White House.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and seized the northern third of the island following an Athens-backed
coup. 
</P>
