<HEADLINE> Turkey Asked to Restrict Military Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Massoud Barzani, leader of the
Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP), has sent letters to the heads
of state of Turkey, the United States, France, Germany and
Britain, asking them to restrict Turkish military operations in
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency today quoted a KDP radio
report as saying that Barzani demanded that the military
operations be used in a limited framework.
</P>
<P>
Safin Dizayee, KDP Representative in Ankara, said that they
had given this message to the Turkish Foreign Ministry and they
might be presenting the letter to President Suleyman Demirel.
</P>
<P>
The KDP Ankara office said in a written statement that since
early April there have been aerial operations and military
incursions into northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It said: "These operations are done under the pretext of the
pursuit of the Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) and targeting
suspected camps."
</P>
<P>
"Sadly in many such operations civilian settlements have fallen
victim to these unnecessary raids," it added. "If such
indiscriminate attacks continue, it will further encourage people
to abandon their homes and create a real vacuum which can only be
an advantage for the PKK."
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 12-year guerrilla war for
self-rule in southeastern Turkey and the PKK rebels have been
penetrating from their camps in northern Iraq for attacking
civilian and military targets in Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
