<HEADLINE> Cyprus Succeeds in Withdrawing Stolen Relic from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government today
succeeded in withdrawing a stolen ancient relic from an auction in
London.
</P>
<P>
According to a police announcement here today, a delegation
from Cyprus Criminal Investigation Department (CID) went to London
following a report that an ancient item stolen from Cyprus
will be auctioned in London.
</P>
<P>
Together with the metropolitan police, the CID officials
managed to avert the sale of the east Greek Geometric Skyphos
of the late 8th century B.C., believed to have been stolen
from a private collection in the Turkish-occupied area of
Famagusta, in the eastern part of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The auctioneers, who told Cyprus last week they were ready to
off help if there was proof concerning the stolen item, decided
to withdraw the stolen antiquity from today's sale.
</P>
<P>
According to the police, investigations are continuing to
locate the seller of the Skyphos.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that a number of antiquities, including
Byzantine icons, were located at auctions or private collections
throughout the world, following the Turkish invasion in 1974,
which led to the division of the island.
</P>
<P>
The government and the church of Cyprus have managed to
secure the return of a number of items belonging to the
island's 9,000-year-old cultural heritage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
