<HEADLINE> IMF Approves 358 Mln Dlr EFF Credit for Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has approved a three-year credit for Peru in an amount of
about 358 million U.S. dollars equivalent under the extended Fund
faciltiy (EFF).
</P>
<P>
The credit is provided to support the Peruvian government's
1996-98 medium-term economic and reform program. About 215 million
dollars equivalent will be available for disbursement during the
first year of the credit.
</P>
<P>
Peru's medium-term strategy aims at consolidating the gains
achieved during 1993-95 by lowering inflation to industrial nation
level by the end of the program period; by creating conditions for
sustained real output growth, which will rise to at least 6
percent by 1998 from 3 to 4.5 percent in 1996; and by
consolidating progress toward external viability by reducing the
external current account deficit to below 5 percent of GDP in 1998
from 7.2 percent of GDP in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The program for 1996 is targeted at containing inflation at 9.5
to 11.5 percent and at narrowing the external current account
deficit to 5.7 percent of GDP. Real GDP growth is expected to be 3
to 4.5 percent this year and the overall deficit of the combined
public sector will be halved to 1.3 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Peru joined the IMF in December 1945. Its quota is about 672
million dollars equivalent and its outstanding use of IMF credit
currently totals about 926 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-04 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes U.S. Officials to Visit Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today welcomed the
forthcoming visit by U.S. presidential Emissary for Cyprus Richard
Beattie and U.S. Ambassador to the U.N. Madeleine Albright,
viewing it as an indication of increased American interest in the
Cyprus question.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, government spokesman
Yiannakis Cassoulides said that the visit will give the chance
to Albright "to be informed about the Cyprus question."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the Cyprus government expects to be briefed
on the U.S. Undersecretary of State Peter Tarnoff's recent
contacts in Athens with the Greek government.
</P>
<P>
However, Cassoulides noted that Cyprus does not consider
visits to this region by high ranking American officials as an
indication that the U.S. sees the Cyprus question as part of the
Greek-Turkish disputes.
</P>
<P>
Cassoulides made the statement ahead of the scheduled visit to
Cyprus by Beattie and Albright in mid July.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the proximity talks between the Greek
and Turkish Cypriot sides to prepare the ground for direct
negotiations "should be confidential if they are to succeed."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the Turkish side would agree to
confidentiality but acknowledged that the matter has not been
discussed.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and seized the northern third of the island following a
short-lived coup by some Greek Cypriots seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community's peace efforts over the
past 22 years have not succeeded in bringing the two sides on the
island closer to an agreement to settle the protracted Cyprus
problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
