<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Advised to Develop Human </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- African states have been advised
to make concerted efforts in promoting human capital particularly
among women, in order to realize better productivity and
sustainable rural development.
</P>
<P>
This was said by resident representative of the U. N.
Development Program (UNDP) in Uganda Babatunde Thomas yesterday
when opening the 4-week post graduates course on human rights of
women in Mukono, about 30 km east of Kampala, reported Radio
Uganda today.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Thomas said gender disparities cut across
employment and income level of Africa where women represent only
14 percent of employees in administrative and management
positions while only 10 percent are members of parliament and
only 6 percent in cabinet posts.
</P>
<P>
The course is in response to the increasing need for an
academic forum to address issues of inequality and violence and
provide information to women leaders on their rights under the
existing international standards according to the U.N. legal
instrument.
</P>
<P>
The course is aimed at increasing awareness of women's legal
literacy in respect of policy in order to eliminate gender bias.
</P>
