<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian PM on Foreign Exchange Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Meles Zenawi
said today the Ethiopian Government Bank, the National Bank and
private banks will gradually be authorized to buy and sell
foreign currencies in free market.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the House of People's Representatives, Meles said
the procedure that obliges traders engaged in export trade to
transfer wholly the foreign exchange they obtain to the National
Bank has had a negative impact on the export trade.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian premier was quoted by the Ethiopian News Agency
as saying that the procedure will gradually be lifted in three
years' time beginning next September.
</P>
<P>
A new procedure will be adopted after two months to allow the
traders to retain ten percent of the foreign exchange they earn
for themselves and sell the remaining for any bank they choose in
three weeks time, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Meles said the foreign exchange auction held fortnightly by
the National Bank will be conducted every week, adding the
auction will gradually stop with the consolidation of the foreign
exchange transaction of both government and private banks.
</P>
<P>
He further said the foreign exchange rate is expected to
stabilize when citizens are allowed to buy from banks any amount
of foreign currency they need for education, health and
miscellaneous expenses in their stay abroad.
</P>
<P>
He added that since a 7.7 percent economic growth rate has
been registered this Ethiopian year (ending on July 7, 1996) and
the inflation rate is lower, the prices of fuel, medicines and
fertilizers will be determined by the world and local markets in
the coming three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
