<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Financing for Eight Projects in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 4 (Xinhua) --The World Bank has recently
approved nine loans and credits for eight projects in Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
A total of 150 million U.S. dollars in financing will be
provided for China's Yunnan environmental protection project. The
financing includes two parts: a 125 million dollar loan and a 25
million dollar credit which will be channeled by the International
Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's concessionary
lending arm for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
China's project will set the stage for Yunnan province's
long-term economic and social development by designing a system of
urban management that includes a sustainable environmental
framework with strategies for urban environmental improvement and
industrial pollution control.
</P>
<P>
Thailand will receive two loans totaling 113.5 million dollars
for its education projects. A 81.9 million dollar loan will be
provided for Thailand to help improve secondary education quality
and another 31.6 million dollar loan will be utilized to support
an expansion of its major technical college and the establishment
of 75 new vocation colleges and polytechnics in the country.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank will provide a 59.6 million dollar loan for
India Uttar Pradesh Rural Water Supply and Environmental
Sanitation Project. The project will deliver sustainable health
and hygiene services to the rural population of Uttar Pradesh
through improvements in water supply and sanitation services.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's Strategic Urban Roads Infrastructure project will
receive a 86.9 million dollar loan from the World Bank. The
project is aimed at improving and upgrading the existing road
networks which will increase transport activities and smooth
traffic flows near major urban centers.
</P>
<P>
The Bank has approved a 180 million dollar loan for Kazakstan's
Financial Sector Adjustment project. The project provides funding
for the government's program to build a sound and efficient
banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Another Central Asian nation Kyrgyz will obtain two IDA credits
totaling 48.4 million dollars. One credit of 45 million dollars
will be provided for Kyrgyz financial sector reform and another
one totaling 3.4 million dollars is provided for the country's
financial sector technical assistance project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
