<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6,500 Burundi Refugees Fled to Zaire, Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Some 6,500 refugees have fled to
Zaire and Rwanda since last weekend due to ethnic clashes in the
Cibitoke region in northwest Burundi, the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) said today.
</P>
<P>
The clashes have also left many houses burnt down and about
22,000 people homeless. Water supplies have been destroyed
and the lack of water has led to outbreaks of disease.
</P>
<P>
Food, medicine, blankets and water are urgently needed, UNHCR
spokesperson Ron Redmond quoted officials of the Burundian
Ministry of Defense as saying.
</P>
<P>
Redmond said that the Burundian government has asked his agency
to help the people in Cibitoke, and UNHCR is considering
sending a fact-finding mission to the area in the next few days
when security conditions allow.
</P>
<P>
There has been no international presence in the Cibitoke region
since three delegates of the International Committee of the Red Cross
were killed in an ambush on June 4.
</P>
<P>
Redmond said about 500 Burundian refugees from a total of 2,500
in Bujarama, southwest Rwanda, had returned to Cibitoke in the
last two days. UNHCR is continuing talks with Rwandan
authorities to move the rest of the Burundi refugees to safer
places away from the border.
</P>
<P>
More than 3,500 refugees from Burundi have arrived In Uvira,
eastern Zaire, since last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Redmond said there were unconfirmed reports of massacres.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
