<HEADLINE> Johnson Says Fredericks is No Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- American sprinter Michael Johnson,
who is attempting to become the first man to win the 200 and 400
meters at one Olympic Games, said his Namibian rival Frank
Fredericks could hardly challenge him or American runners in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Fredericks, 200 meters runner-up in the Barcelona Games four
years ago, will square off with Johnson in an international meet
in Oslo on Friday, and fans are considering it an Olympic preview.
</P>
<P>
Johnson begged to disagree.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not (considering so)," said Johnson. "A lot can happen
between now and the Olympic 200 meters final on August 1. For me,
this is just another race before the Games. I am using it to work
on some things, to stay sharp and to keep focused."
</P>
<P>
"I understand the interest," he said. "I am coming off a world
record in the 200 (19.66 seconds) at the U.S. trials. Frankie has
run the two fastest 100 times of the year, 9:86 and 9:87, just off
the world record of 9:85.
</P>
<P>
"Frankie has not run many 200s this year. He's run 19:95, but
three others -- myself, also Ato Boldon and Mike Marsh -- have
gone under 19.9. Impressive 100 times don't always transfer to the
200.
</P>
<P>
"If I have to, I'm ready to run 19.6 or 19.7. I don't think
Frankie is ready to run those times."
</P>
<P>
Fredericks said earlier that he was not sure what he was going
to run in Atlanta, either the 100/200 double or just the 200.
</P>
<P>
Johnson thought Federicks would do double.
</P>
<P>
"Frankie will run both the 100 and 200," Johnson said. "He'd be
fool not to. He's got to run the 100; he's almost broken the world
record twice. Then he has three days of rest before starting the 200.
So he's got to run the 200."
</P>
<P>
Johnson added that he still wanted to win although the outcome
of Friday's 200 would not determine the Olympic 200 champion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
