<HEADLINE> Ukraine Urges Russia to Resume Bilateral Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine today urged Russia to resume
bilateral negotiations on a series of controversial issues, talks
which had been put on hold by the Russian presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian Foreign Minister Gennady Udovenko said on Wednesday
that he was satisfied with the result of the second round of the
election and Ukraine's policy of backing incumbent president Boris
Yeltsin had proved correct.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin won the election with 54 percent of the vote, beating
his political rival Gennady Zyuganov by 13 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko said it's the time for the two countries to take
active measures to settle the controversial issues between them,
notably the Black Sea Fleet issue.
</P>
<P>
A solution acceptable to both sides should be found through
joint efforts, Udovenko stressed.
</P>
<P>
Most of the differences between Ukraine and Russia over the
division of the fleet, a legacy left over from the former Soviet
Union, have been settled.
</P>
<P>
But there is still the unresolved question of whether the
Russian navy will be allowed to use the military port of
Sevastopol, inside Ukrainian territory.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Ukraine said it may lease the port to the
Russian navy, but the two sides have never reached agreement on
the time limit and rent of the lease.
</P>
<P>
The two countries failed to sign an agreement of friendship,
cooperation and partnership, expected three years ago, due to the
above disputes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
