<HEADLINE> Oath-Taking Ceremony of Afghan Cabinet Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The oath-taking ceremony of the
new Afghan cabinet, which had been scheduled for Thursday evening,
was put off for an indefinite period, said a report reaching here
today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted observers as saying that the postponement
resulted from differences between Afghan new Prime Minister
Gulbuddin Hekmatyar and President Burhanuddin Rabbani over some
nominees of the ministers of state.
</P>
<P>
Hekmatyar, Hezb-i-Islami leader and one of the arch rivals of
Rabbani, reconciliated with Rabbani recently and took oath as
prime minister of a new coalition government in Kabul last
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A week later, Hekmatyar appointed nine ministers of his
26-portfolio cabinet and Rabbani's spokesman Abdul Aziz Mural said
that the nine ministers would be sworn in on Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
Among the fixed nine positions, two would be taken by
Hekmatyar's Hezb-i-Islami, one by Rabbani's Jamiat-i-Islami, two
by Ittehad-i-Islami led by Rasoul Sayyaf who has allied with
Rabbani for many years, and the rest by other small allied
parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
