<HEADLINE> NPC Chairman Meets Myanmese Attorney General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Qiao Shi, chairman of the Chinese
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, met in
Beijing today with a Myanmese delegation headed by U Tha Tun, the
Attorney General of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Describing Sino-Myanmese relations as "quite good," Qiao said
he hopes that the two countries' ties will be further promoted on
the basis of the Five Principles of Peaceful Co-existence.
</P>
<P>
China has always insisted that the state-to-state relations
should be handled under the Five Principles of Peaceful
Co-existence, Qiao told U Tha Tun, adding that China is willing to
strengthen its links with Myanmar -- one of China's important
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The chairman also briefed the Myanmese visitors on China's
development of democracy and legal system in the process of
establishing socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the delegation's current China visit will help
enhance the cooperation between the procuratorial organs of the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
U Tha Tun told Qiao that Myanmar's foreign policy is also based
on the Five Principles of Peaceful Co-existence, which were
initiated by the two countries. Myanmar hopes to reinforce its
friendly and cooperative ties with its surrounding countries,
especially with China, He added.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes that the bilateral cooperation in the field of
legal affairs will be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Siqing, Procurator-General of China's Supreme People's
Procuratorate, held work talks with U Tha Tun, who is visiting
China as Zhang's guest. 
