<HEADLINE> Malaysian Plastics Industry to Grow by 8.3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's plastics industry
is expected to grow by 8.3 percent in 1996, Minister of
International Trade and Industry Rafidah Aziz said today.
</P>
<P>
According to a speech by the minister, the country's plastics
industry had recorded double-digit growth rates from 1991 to 1995,
averaging at 13.4 percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah's speech was read by the ministry's parliament
secretary Hishamuddin Tun Hussein at the Malaysian Plastic
Manufacturers' Association tonight.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the plastics industry recorded an estimated turnover
of about five billion Malaysian ringgit (about two billion US
dollars), an increase of 19 percent from 1994.
</P>
<P>
"This increase has been mainly attributed to the increased
demand by domestic companies," the speech read.
</P>
<P>
The country's exports of plastic products also went up by 23
percent in 1995, reaching 1.35 billion ringgit (about 540 million
dollars) against 1.1 billion ringgit (about 440 million dollars)
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
However, Rafidah urged plastic manufacturers to make efforts to
widen their markets. She said Malaysian companies should not look
only at the domestic market, noting that the Malaysian plastics
industry has gained only a very small portion of the market of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Malaysia's intra-ASEAN trade in 1995
amounted to 84 billion ringgit (about 33.6 billion US dollars),
constituting about 25 percent of the intra-ASEAN trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
