<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Urges Moscow to be Flexible Over Territorial Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- In the wake of Russia's presidential
election, Japan today urged Moscow to be more flexible on a
long-standing territorial dispute over four islands and said it
would activate bilateral talks on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Yukihiko Ikeda told a press conference that
Tokyo wants to start bilateral talks on the four Russian-held
islands off Japan's northernmost main island of Hokkaido.
</P>
<P>
The islands -- Etorofu, Kunashiri, Shikotan and the Habomai
group of islets -- were seized by the Soviet Union at the end of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
Japan has since demanded the return of the islands as a
prerequisite to the conclusion of a bilateral peace treaty.
Moscow has so far flatly rejected the demand.
</P>
<P>
Ikeda also said Japan hopes political and economic reforms
will continue with President Boris Yeltsin's re-election.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's emphatic victory in Wednesday's run-off election over
his political rival Gennady Zyuganov shows that Russian people
support Yeltsin's reform-oriented policies, he said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin won 54 percent of the votes, beating Zyuganov by 13
percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
