<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto is
scheduled to leave here for Europe Sunday for a routine medical
check-up, Minster/State Secretary Moerdiono announced today,
following mounting speculations about the president's health.
</P>
<P>
The 75-year-old head of state "will go abroad with the main aim
of undergoing a medical check-up," Moerdiono told journalists
here, but he declined to specify which country it would be.
</P>
<P>
He said the president was advised to go abroad by his doctors
after a regular check-up on June 26.
</P>
<P>
The doctors advised further check-ups using "more sophisticated
equipment than those available in the country."
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, sources close to ministers said that the president
would go for treatment in Germany, possibly in the city of
Frankfurt, for his health problems.
</P>
<P>
Moerdiono said check-ups in foreign countries were "something
normal" as many officials do so.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was hospitalized briefly in August 1994 when he was
found to have a stone in the left urinary tract.
</P>
<P>
His urinary problems dated back to 1982 when he underwent an
operation at a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Indonesian rupiah dropped against the US dollar
in trading in Singapore today as Jakarta confirmed that the
president was traveling to Europe for a medical check-up.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was changing hands at 2,344-2,346 rupiah this
afternoon from an opening quote of 2,335 in Singapore, Asia's
leading trading center for regional currencies, dealers said.
