<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First International Conference on Joyce's "Ulysses" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Scholars and other people
interested in James Joyce gathered in Beijing today to discuss the
Irish writer's life and works.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Hayes, Irland's ambassador to China, said at the opening
of the first International Academic Conference on James Joyce in
China that people attending the meeting could "share a common love
of the values and spirit of great literature."
</P>
<P>
Although the author's "Ulysses" was known to many Chinese in
the 1930s, publication of a Chinese version of the entire work did
not come until the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Nearly one hundred scholars and publishers attending the
conference reached consensus that the meeting was a superb
opportunity for Chinese literature to meld with world literature.
</P>
<P>
In a congratulatory letter to the translator of the Chinese
version of "Ulysses", Irland's President Mary Robinson expressed
her thanks to Jin Di for his "16-year labor of love in bringing to
the billion users of Chinese a work of art which is generally
regarded as the greatest English language literary achievement of
the 20th century."
</P>
<P>
She also wished the conference success.
</P>
<P>
Joyce wrote "Ulysses" in 1922, an example of the
stream-of-consciousness genre and a pioneer of modernist
novels. The work was controversial worldwide after its publication
and was banned by many countries.
</P>
<P>
Before the reforms and opening-up, China also banned modernist
novels, including "Ulysses", and those who even read Western
literature secretely were accused of being dangerous elements
until 1978, when the country began to re-evaluate and re-introduce
the genre.
</P>
<P>
Now, people are able to buy and openly discuss novels and poems
by Jean-Paul Sartre, Franz Kafka, and Thomas Stearns Eliot.
</P>
<P>
In 1981 Jin Di, a professor at the Tianjin Foreign Studies
University, translated a few chapters of "Ulysses" and got them
published, then in 1993, he published the first volume of the work
itself.
</P>
<P>
Another Chinese version of the book was done by Xiao Qian and
his wife, Wen Ruojie, both experienced translators.
</P>
<P>
The two versions of the work are said to have been printed
millions of times in the Chinese mainland, Taiwan and Hong Kong,
but many scholars and ordinary people are interested in comparing
their translation skills by examining the truthfulness,
expressiveness, and graceful qualities.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yuanmai, director of the Foreign Literature Institute of the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, says that, in spite of the
disputes, publication of the Chinese version of "Ulysses" itself
was a great event in China's cultural life.
</P>
<P>
Chen Wei, another researcher, says that publication would have
been impossible "if there had been no great change in Chinese
society and the economy."
</P>
<P>
According to Wu, history has proven that excellent works can
break down barriers of time and space. Readers from various eras
should be allowed to share different ideas about literary works
based on their needs and aesthetic judgments, and many scholars
believe that "Ulysses" is a gift for Chinese civilization.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Kejia, a well-known translator, has this to say, "The
exchange between and supplement to both (Chinese and Western)
sides will make world literature all the more rich and
splendid. This is where the significance of this conference lies."
</P>
<P>
He also notes, however, that owing to the great differences
that exist between Western and Oriental cultures, it is certainly
no easy job for China to profit from Modernism.
</P>
<P>
"A patient process of explication, discrimination and digestion
is evidently in need," he points out.
</P>
<P>
People attending today's meeting included representatives from
the International James Joyce Foundation, researchers from Europe
and America, as well as experts from Taiwan and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Professor Jin Di delivered a report at the meeting, but the
other translator, Xiao Qian, was unable to attend because of
illness.
</P>
<P>
The conference was jointly held by the Tianjin Foreign Studies
University, the Foreign Literature Institute of CASS, the Embassy
of Ireland, and other relevant institutes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Insurance Company Opens Outlet in Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A big Canadian insurance company,
Manulife, has opened an outlet in Macao, paving the way for
entering the life insurance market in China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
Victor Apps, a top executive of Manulife, said at an opening
ceremony here on Thursday that his company aims to take some 10
percent of the local life insurance market in Macao in three
years.
</P>
<P>
One of the biggest life insurance company in Canada, Manulife
tapped the Asia market from 1897 with Hong Kong as its base. Its
main targets are life insurance markets in China's mainland, Macao
and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Another top executive of the company said that his company
hopes to expand its business into Zhuhai City bordering Macao, and
the Pearl River Delta, following its development in Macao.
</P>
<P>
"To open an outlet in Macao is an necessary and strategic
decision of our company," the executive said.
</P>
<P>
With the entry of Manulife, the number of life insurance
companies in Macao has increased to five.  
</P>
</TEXT>
