<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accelerated Payment of Tax Rebates in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Rebates of taxes for exporters rose
nearly 175 percent to more than 13 billion yuan (more than one and
a half billion US dollars) in May, reversing a downward trend in
the first four months of the year, a senior official of the State
Administration of Taxation said here today.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Faguang, deputy director-general of SAT quoted the latest
statistics showing that China's tax rebates for exports reached
34.4 billion yuan by June 20, up 7.1 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Cheng estimated China's tax rebates to exporters by the end of
June at some 40 billion yuan. This year's budgeted figure is 65
billion yuan and to date 63.6 billion yuan has been allocated.
</P>
<P>
During the January-April period, China's tax system paid
exporters a total of 15.63 billion yuan in rebates, down 42
percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
To stop the slide, SAT issued two notices in May and June,
urging tax departments nationwide to speed up payment of rebates
to exporters, and lifted the annual tax rebate quota by 7.5
billion yuan, setting aside another 1.5 billion yuan especially
for exporters of textile and silk products.
</P>
<P>
Cheng explained that "accelerated payment of tax rebates since
May will greatly boost China's exports and help ease the pressure
of a capital shortage confronted by exporting enterprises."
</P>
</TEXT>
