<HEADLINE> Graf Enters Her Eight Wimbledon Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WIMBLEDON, ENGLAND, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion
Steffi Graf of Germany has gained a difficult victory over her
strong-willed Japanese opponent Kimiko Date and entered the her
eight Wimbledon final here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
World number one Graf has met with fierce opposition from the
12th-seeded Date, who is slow starter at all matches at the
Wimbledon tournament.
</P>
<P>
During the first two set played on Thursday, Date, lost her
first set 2-6, launched powerful counterattcks upon her arch-rival
and grabbed the second set by the same 6-2.
</P>
<P>
When the Japanese player seemed totally dominated the Wimbledon
Center Court and forced the defending champion on the defensive,
the matches were suspended due to the falling of dusk.
</P>
<P>
At the crucial third set played early this morning, Graf, fully
recovered from her disadvantageous situation on Thursday, turned
the tables and won the third set 6-3. But slow-starter and unlucky
Date could certainly learn a lot and also gain much confidence
from the match against Graf.
</P>
<P>
The German tennis ace is due to meet with Arantxa Sanchchez of
Spain at the Wimbledon women's singles final, which a re-play of
the 1995 Wimbledon women's singles final.
</P>
<P>
Sanchez Vicario cruised into the final Thursday by beating
Meredith McGrath 6-2, 6-1 in 61 minutes.
</P>
<P>
It will be the seventh Grand Slam final between Graf and
Sanchez Vicario. Last month, Graf beat the Spaniard in three sets
for the French Open title. 
</P>
