<HEADLINE> Foreign Technology For Heilongjiang's Saline-alkali Soil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Heilongjiang
Province has succeeded in transforming 133 hectares of
saline-alkali land using a biochemical technique imported from the
Republic of Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
This key agricultural producing area plans to apply the
technique, which uses a type of forage grass for planting in
saline-alkali soil, all across the province next year. The grass
is used not only to feed animals, but also enriches the soil.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang's saline-alkali soil, covering 930,000 hectares,
is mainly found in the plain areas, where the Songhua and Nenjiang
rivers meet. Over-grazing of grassland for years has upset the
ecology, causing 70 percent of the grassland to deteriorate.
</P>
