<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: HK to Be Brighter for ROK Businessmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Businessmen from the Republic of
Korea (ROK) hold that Hong Kong's investment and market
environment will be brighter in the coming years, said Paek
Chong-Hyon, chairman of the Korean Chamber of Commerce in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Xinhua, Paek said South Korean
businessmen's confidence in Hong Kong can be testified by the
increasing number of enterprises run by Koreans in Hong Kong in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
According to the chamber, in 1985, there were only 16 South
Korean investment enterprises in Hong Kong, and now the number
exceeds 250.
</P>
<P>
Paek said the total number of South Korean companies in Hong
Kong has reached more than 400 with 76 large enterprises setting
regional headquarters in the territory.
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong has become South Korea's eighth largest
overseas investment destination and that by the end of last year,
his country's investment in Hong Kong amounted to 324 million US
dollars. The amount will be rising in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Paek said trade between South Korea and Hong Kong has grown
rapidly in recent years, and it rose by 32.8 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is South Korea's third largest destination for its
exports and as an international trade center, Hong Kong will in
future be more important for South Korea's exports which will be
delivered to China's mainland and Southeast Asian countries, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Paek said Hong Kong also serves as a major source of investment
for South Korea, adding that about 35 percent of the country's
funds were collected from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
With many South Korean companies in Hong Kong turning to open
up market in the Chinese mainland, Hong Kong is becoming more
important for them to collect funds to promote their business in
China, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Now about 100 Hong Kong-based ROK (Republic of Korea)
enterprises are engaged in electronic, textile and chemical
industries in Chinese mainland and they have made progress in
business," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that with Hong Kong's return to China and the
implementation of the principle of "one country, two systems",
Hong Kong's economy will become more vigorous.
</P>
<P>
He said his chamber and South Korean companies will enhance
their cooperation with their Hong Kong counterparts and will also
increase their investment in the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
He said that in future, South Korea's strategy for trade
development is to open emerging markets in Asia with a focus on
the market in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
