<HEADLINE> No Food Deficits in Coming Year, Says Tanzanian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A total of 7.393 million
tonnes of food crop harvests is expected for the financial year
1995/96 against an originally stipulated target of 7.084 tonnes.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Agriculture and Co-operatives Paul Kimiti said on
Thursday that available statistics show there is likely to be no
food deficits in the coming year except for wheat. The minister
made the statement when he presented the 1996/97 budget to the
National Assembly on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that yields of some 4.476 million tonnes of
grain and 2.608 million tonnes of other food crops were expected
to be harvested in this financial year, owing to excellent
weather and other conditions in the past year.
</P>
<P>
A surplus of 310,000 tonnes of non-grain food crops can be
sold abroad without disrupting supply to suffice the national
food demand before the next harvesting season, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kimiti predicted that in the 1996/97 fiscal year, cotton
yields will increase by 102 per ceent, coffee by 27 percent,
cashewnuts by 22 percent and sugar by 8.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The minister told that in the last fiscal year sisal
production decreased slightly, while tea production decreased by
nine percent and pyrethrum yields descended to 18 percent of the
previous year's crop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
