<HEADLINE> Cyprus Launches National Policy Against Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government has launched
a national policy against drugs with special emphasis on the
protection of young people against the menace.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the national anti-drug policy at a special
launching ceremony Thursday night in Nicosia, President Glafcos
Clerides said a coordinating body has been set up to study the
problem and seek ways of solution.
</P>
<P>
This coordinating body, which involves the President himself,
the Council of Ministers, ministries, youth and anti-narcotic
organizations, will also be responsible for the supervision of
programs aimed at the prevention of drugs abuses, the President
added.
</P>
<P>
He promised that programs for treating addicts will be
upgraded and that efforts to rehabilitate them into society
intensified.
</P>
<P>
President Clerides congratulated the Cyprus police and
especially the anti-drug squad for their success in stamping out
drug-trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Minister for Justice and Public
Order Alecos Evangelou said though the drug related problems in
Cyprus were not so serious so far, but there was always the danger
of exacerbation.
</P>
<P>
Referring to legal measures against drugs, Evangelou said the
Justice Ministry is in a process of legislation in line with
international conventions.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government has recently stepped up its anti-drug
campaign as the drug cases have been on the increase in the past
few years.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics issued by the police, in 1995 the
authorities investigated 156 drug cases involving 221 people, with
100 being Cypriots. However, in 1990 there were just 50 cases
involving 79 people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
