<HEADLINE> Uganda Starts Operation To Put Down Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 5 (Xinhua)-- Uganda has started an offensive to
wipe out rebels of the Lard's Resistance Army in the north,
reported local daily "The New Vision" today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Salim Saleh, a presidential advisor on
political and military affairs as saying that the operation will
last six months.
</P>
<P>
"We are occupying all the rebel bases, their resting bases and
transit routes. This will keep the rebels constantly on the
move," Saleh said.
</P>
<P>
The occupied rebel areas cover key bases, caves, hills and
forest areas around Kilak Hills and Kilak game reserves.
</P>
<P>
Also occupied are Ayugi forest reserves, Akara Hills in Achwa
County and Mogali Ridges bordering Sudan, he said.
</P>
<P>
The 401 brigade headquarters of the Uganda army has since June
19 moved to Kilak Hills to carry out the crack down, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kilak Hills are the scene of a protracted gurrilla warfair in
which the Acholi Tribe fought against the British colonialists,
known as the Lamogi Rebellion.
</P>
<P>
Saleh said that there are other areas to be occupied soon. The
next stage will start to use more "harder ways", including
confiscating properties of suspected rebel agents and their
collaborators, to end the insurgency there, he added.
</P>
<P>
All means are devised to stop the rebels from bringing in more
arms and supplies from Sudan, Saleh said.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni in his April campaign for
presidency pledged to voters in the north that he will stage an
offensive to wipe out rebels in the north in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
