<HEADLINE> India's United Front Leaders Concerned Over Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of India's ruling United
Front today expressed serious concern over the steep hike in
petroleum products and urged Prime Minister H.D. Deve Gowda to
immediately reconsider the decision, the Press Trust of India
said.
</P>
<P>
The issue of price hike, which was announced by the government
on Tuesday, came up for discussion at an hour-long meeting of the
13-party front's steering committee at the prime minister's
residence here this morning.
</P>
<P>
United Front sources said the leaders, including chief
ministers such as Jyoti Basu, Laloo Prasad Yadav and Chandrababu
Naidu, are understood to have conveyed their reservations over the
steep hike which they felt would hit the common man the most and
have a cascading effect on prices.
</P>
<P>
According to the government announcement, price of petrol went
up by 25 percent while those of diesel and domestic cooling gas by
30 percent from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The steering committee is against schedule to meet in the
evening after an expected cabinet expansion today, the sources
said.  
