<HEADLINE> Swazi Actling Prime Minister Warns Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Acting Prime Minister of
Swaziland, Sishayi Nxumalo, has warned the Swazi People against
the growing trend of using wildcat industrial action as a weapon
to force government to meet unbudgeted salary increase demands,
South African daily ''The Citizen'' reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Swazi prime miniser was referring to the demand by the
country's teachers and civil servants currently on strike for
salary hike.
</P>
<P>
Swazi teachers and civil servants staged a wildcat strike last
month, demanding a 18 percent salary increase. But the government
was offering them a 9.9 percent plus a four percent increase in
allowances.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in the capital Mbabene on
Thursday, Nxumalo said if the strikers' demand are granted, the
money will have to come from funds earmarked for development
projects to improve the quality of life of people in the rural
areas where the majority of the population are unemployed and
with no salary at all.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is deeply concerned about the widening
gap between the vast majority of the Swazi people who are without
jobs and the fortunate minority with jobs, salaries and
allowances and still demanding more.
</P>
<P>
To this regard, the Acting prime minster noted, these
midguided demands by labour organisations especially in these
times of national economic difficulties undermined the
government's efforts to speed up development in the rural areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
