<HEADLINE> Japanese Cabinet Advocates Higher Retirement Age </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese cabinet has endorsed
lifting the retirement age from 60 to 65 as part of a new 10-year
outline to cope with the rapid graying of the Japanese society,
Kyodo News Service quoted government officials as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
The outline, a follow-up to last year's law on measures to cope
with the graying of the society, is setting comprehensive
guidelines for policy-making in this area over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
The basic idea is to create an environment that enables elderly
citizens to live independently and to participate actively in
society.
</P>
<P>
By encouraging private initiative and making existing
facilities more efficient, the outline aims to "control the
increase of taxpayers' burden in the future as much as possible."
</P>
<P>
A major means for easing the fiscal burden resulting from the
rise in the number of pensioners would be to secure employment
opportunities of various kinds beyond the current retirement age
of 60, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The outline also calls for the introduction of a public nursing
care insurance for the elderly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
