<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Govt Urged To Speed Refugee Repatriation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
( by Guo Ming)
</P>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Organisation of African Unity
(OAU) today urged the Tutsi-led Rwandan government to adopt a
policy of national reconciliation to ensure early repatriation of
its 1.7 million Hutu refugees.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts should be stepped up by the Rwandan government to
build a condusive atmosphere for early repatriation of refugees
in order to ensure peace, stability and security in the country
and in the sub-region," said a resolution passed by the ongoing
64th council of ministers meeting.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda, with its refugee population totaling 1.7 million, is
on top of the list of the 1996 refugee report recently released
by the United Nations High Commissioner of Refugees (UNHCR).
</P>
<P>
The death of Rwandan President Juvenal Habyramana and his
Burundi counterpart President Cyprian Ntaryamira following the
downing of their aircrft, started a massive ethnic massacre of
the minority Tutsis by then Hutu government, resulting in huge
exdos of refugees.
</P>
<P>
Between 500,000 and a million minority Tutsis and moderate
Hutus were butchered between April and July in 1994, until the
Tutsi-dominated rebel Rwanda Patriotic Front defeated the old
Hutu government and took power.
</P>
<P>
The Tutsi government insistence that properties be returned to
their original owners has often been ignored by local authorities
who favor newcomers over returnees tainted by the genocide.
</P>
<P>
"The massacres have gone so deep, it is difficult to find
forgiveness." said the United Nations special representative
Shaharyar Khan.
</P>
<P>
The OAU also called on asylum countries, including Zaire,
Burundi and Tanzania, to make further sacrefices for the welfare
and needs of the Rwandan refugees.
</P>
<P>
Few of the 1.7 million Rwandan Hutu refugees who fled to
Zaire, Tanzania and Burundi have come back home.
</P>
<P>
These victims of intimidation by the former Hutu
administration behind the genocide fear revenge attacks by the
ruling Rwandan Patriotic Front (RPF) of the minority Tutsis on
their return.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan refugees have caused many political, economic and
social problems for the host countries, which have been urging
for their early repatriation.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, the Zairean government threatened the use
of force against the one million Rwandan refugees in its
territory and made an urgent call on the OAU for their prompt
repatriation, saying Zaire's national security is severely
threatened by the armed Rwandan refugees.
</P>
<P>
Analysts warned that the Hutu refugees might develop into a
military force on Rwanda's borders, just as earlier generations
of Tutsi refugees, fleeing after the overthrow of the Tutsi
monarchy in 1959, later formed the Rwanda Patriotic Army which
invaded from Uganda in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The refugee camps just over Rwanda's borders are a potent
source of instability for the former rebels who now make up the
Tutsi-dominated government in Kigali.
</P>
<P>
Zaire had previously threatened to close the camps on its
territory by force, seeing the refugees as causing
destabilisation along its ethnically mixed eastern border.
</P>
<P>
The OAU resolution also urged the international aid
organisations to continue to provide financial assistence to the
governments of Rwanda and the asylum countries to facilitate the
voluntary repatriation of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
Aid has poured in from more than 100 agencies, but there has
been little direct help to the new government from foreign donors
suspicious of the administration in the capital Kigali.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda
(ICTA ) which has been in existence for quite some time now
formally charged the first suspects in late May this year. Lack
of funding for the tribunal is one of the factors accounting for
the slow pace of its operations.
</P>
<P>
The current Tutsi-dominated Rwandan government is holding some
67,000 prisoners on charges related to the 1994 massacres for
trial in Rwanda's own court system, which is barely functioning.
Over 2,000 have already died in overcrowded jails.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. wants to maintain a small political presence in
Rwanda to assist in promoting national reconciliation,
strengthening the judicial system, facilitating return of
refugees and rehabilitating infrastructure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
