<HEADLINE> US Promises No Cut in Aid to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has been given a promise of no
cut in American financial assistance to the largest Middle East
country despite a persistent effort by the U.S.congress to reduce
Washington's foreign aid level.
</P>
<P>
A visiting U.S. official announced here Thursday that the
U.S. financial aid to Egypt would remain at its usual level of 815
million U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sally Shelton, Deputy Director of the U.S. Agency for
International Development, told a press conference that the
U.S. congress was to conclude debates over aid to Egypt and no
reduction had been requested in this case.
</P>
<P>
The congress has stopped foreign aid to some countries because
of budget deficit, said the official who is here to attend a
session of the Education and Human Resources Committee.
</P>
<P>
The committee is an offshoot of the Egyptian-U.S. partnership
agreement known as the Mubarak-Gore Agreement.
</P>
<P>
She called Egypt one of the most important friends to the U.S.,
noting Cairo plays a central role in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the largest U.S aid recipient country second only to
Israel in the Middle East region. It receives 2.3 billion dollars
in terms of economic and military aid annually, about 0.9 billion
dollars less than that by Israel.
</P>
<P>
U.S. plans for assistance to Egypt would center on four main
fields: economic development, infrastructure, population and
health and the promotion of the judicial system and the faculties
of law, she said.
</P>
<P>
However, she added:"Egypt will not need aid for life." 
</P>
</TEXT>
