<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment in Yangtze Delta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The delta area of China's longest
river, which includes Shanghai and parts of Jiangsu and Zhejiang
provinces, has over 55,000 overseas-funded enterprises, including
about half of the world's 100 biggest multinationals.
</P>
<P>
"To invest in the delta area is very profitable," Jean-Pierre
Vassaux, general manager of Shanghai Associated Finance, Ltd, has
commented.
</P>
<P>
That financial venture involving the Shanghai Branch of the
Construction Bank of China and Societe Generale of France made a
profit of 30,000 US dollars in the first year of operation in
1994, and 500,000 US dollars the following year.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai AT&AMP;T, a Sino-US venture, recouped its total investment
of 18 million US dollars within three years of opening in 1991.
</P>
<P>
It was China's first joint venture producing optical fibre
digital transmission equipment and now has 30 percent of the
Chinese market and is involved in building the country's 22
long-distance trunk lines.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-German Shanghai Volkswagen Automotive Company is
another success story. Started in 1985 with registered capital of
350 million yuan (42 million US dollars), it by now has increased
that to 2.3 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The company has sold over 500,000 Santana cars, worth over 60
billion yuan in China, and has been cited as one of China's best
overseas-invested enterprises for three consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
Suzhou Matsushita Electric Works Ltd., a Sino-Japanese venture,
invested 46 million US dollars in March, 1995, to produce
copper-clad laminates and printed boards as parts for Matsushita's
color television and micro-wave oven plants in the delta. The
venture expects to recoup its investment in five years.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Iveco Fiat has decided to invest 400 million US
dollars along with the Jiangsu Yuejin Motor Vehicle Group to
form Naveco Ltd.
</P>
<P>
"We like to see more Iveco cars running in the streets of
China," said Camillo Donati, chief representative of Iveco's China
Office.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that with the constant improving of China's market
economic structure, investors will be more successful in the delta
area," Associated Finance's Vassaux concludes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
