<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Reduce Rice-Growing Land to Save Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian government plans
gradually to reduce rice-cultivating land from present 672,000
million hectares to 294,000 hectares by the year 2000 in a bid to
save water.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Public Works and Water Resources, in
coordination with the Ministry of Agriculture, issued a decree on
May 1, prohibiting many areas in Egypt from cultivating rice, the
latest local English newspaper Al-Ahram Weekly reported.
</P>
<P>
The ban, which will be in effect in June next year, is due to
water shortages, the paper quoted government sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Those who violate the ban will face a fine of 952 Egyptian
pounds (about 281 U.S. dollars) per hectare of illegal rice crop
and 10 pastres (about 0.029 dollars) for each cubic meters of
water used to irrigate the rice, according to the decree.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Hadi Radi, Minister of Public Works and Water resources,
told the paper that Egypt's quota of the Nile River's water is 5.5
billion cubic meters a year.
</P>
<P>
This amount should be sufficient for Egypt's agricultural,
commercial, industrial and household needs, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, the government cannot afford to use 21,429 cubic
meters of water to irrigate one hectare of rice field, Radi said.
</P>
<P>
"If we are not cautious with water, Egypt will be suffering
from a severe water shortage by the year 2025," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Egypt's rice harvest was estimated at 4.8 million
tons, compared with 4.5 million tons in 1994, according to the
paper.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian wholesalers and farmers expect rice production to
decrease drastically after the ban comes into effect.
</P>
<P>
However, Saad Nassar, Head of the Agricultural Research Center,
which is affiliated to the Ministry of Agriculture, said the
ministry will increase the productivity rate to 819 tons per
hectare from the present 571 tons by using new kinds
of fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian farmers were unhappy with the ban and wanting the new
decree to be revoked on the ground that the high price of rice help
them to pay debt which they own to banks, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guizhou Trade Talks in Hong Kong to Be Held as Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment and trade
