<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Bustling Chung Ying Street (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a duty-free zone, the street is known as a "shopper's
paradise" across the country. In addition to daily necessities,
gold jewelry is a hot item for bargain hunters.
</P>
<P>
A young lady choosing gold necklaces in a jewelry store said,
"Hong Kong has the lowest gold price in the world. Buying gold
jewelry on the Sino-British Street is exactly the same as buying
such jewelry in Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
According to the boss of the Boji Store, commodities available
on the street are mostly ordered directly from wholesalers or
manufacturers in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Because of intense competition, prices of many commodities on
the street are even lower than those in Hong Kong," he said.
</P>
<P>
For historical reasons inland residents on one side of the
street have relatives living on the opposite side, in what is Hong
Kong's new territories. It means that residents on both sides of
the street can visit each other frequently.
</P>
<P>
With more and more people coming to the street on shopping
expeditions, more business people from Shatoujiao and Hong Kong
have flocked to the street, where both Chinese currency Renminbi
yuan and Hong Kong dollar are accepted.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years the Shatoujiao Town government, the
Shenzhen City government and the Guangdong provincial government
have financed the construction of a number of large stores on the
street, as well as apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Quanfang, secretary of the Shatoujiao Town Committee of
the Chinese Communist Party, described the street as a "special
zone within a special economic zone."
</P>
<P>
He promised the the Shatoujiao town government will do its
utmost to turn the street into an even better "paradise" for
shopping, sightseeing, tourism, recreation and services.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NEC to Manufacture Flash Memory Chips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Japan's NEC Corp. will start
manufacturing flash memory chips by the end of 1996 to meet the
growing demand for portable products, Kyodo News Service quoted a
company spokesman as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
The company will initially mass produce 4-megabit and 8-megabit
flash memory chips and plan to produce one million units a month.
</P>
<P>
It also plans to start manufacturing 256-megabit flash memory
chips it has developed together with a U.S. maker from the latter
half of 1997, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
NEC will produce flash memories at its production subsidiaries
in Yamaguchi, Hiroshima and Kumamoto prefectures.
</P>
<P>
The production lines for the chips will be shared with those
for 16-megabit dynamic random access memory (DRAM), the production
of which is currently being adjusted, he said.
</P>
<P>
Flash memory chips have the potential for a wide range of
applications such as in digital cameras, portable information and
communication equipment, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
