<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Bustling Chung Ying Street (1) Eds: repeat for cvorrection of the street name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 5 (Xinhua Correspondent Che Xiaohui) -- It's
eight o'clock in the morning Beijing time, and the Chung Ying
Street in Shatoujiao Town, Shenzhen City, Guangdong Province,
begins to bustle.
</P>
<P>
Large numbers of visitors speaking in different accents,
dialects and languages flock to the street from the nearby
Shatoujiao customs office.
</P>
<P>
The street, known as "one street with two social systems,"
quickly becomes noisy, with peddlers hawking their goods, and
would-be buyers haggling with sellers.
</P>
<P>
The street -- 250 meters long and three to four meters wide --
is divided by eight boundary tablets at its center. Crossing the
tablets means crossing borders. The middle line of the street
forms the dividing line between China's inland area and Hong
Kong's New Territories.
</P>
<P>
Here visitors shop freely in any store on either side of the
street.
</P>
<P>
A special environment has turned the street into a commercial
and tourism center, with nearly 200 stores and shops.
</P>
<P>
Some 20,000 people from all over the country converge on the
street for shopping and sightseeing every day, according to the
local customs office.
</P>
<P>
The Boji Grocery is considered the busiest store on the
street. Its floor space of just 20 square meters is packed with
foodstuffs, detergents, cosmetics and kitchen utensils. There is
always a queue at the cashier's check-out.
</P>
<P>
A man carrying a basket of goods was in the line. He said with
a strong northeast China accent: "I think Chung Ying Street is a
place that all people coming to Shenzhen must visit. Besides, it
is less expensive to do your shopping on the street, where prices
of goods are usually 33 percent lower than elsewhere."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberalisation Policy Makes Tanzania's Cash Crop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Liberalisation of cash crops
marketing, a policy which was introduced two years ago, has
increased the cotton and coffee production.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by Tanzanian Minister for Agriculture
and Co-operatives Paul Kimiti at a National Assembly meeting on
Thursday. He said that liberalised cash crops marketing had
pushed up producers' prices in many parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Kimiti said that cotton production increased from 148,953 tonnes in
1994/95 to 251,200 tonnes in 1995/96, while the output at
ginning factories and coffee curing plants also went up during the period.
</P>
<P>
He said plans are underway to liberalise marketing of tea,
pyrethrum and sisal and a law to that effect will be moved in
the National Assembly later in the 1996/97 financial year.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the move was designed to increase
competition among buyers, a factor that was anticipated to push
up producers' prices, much in the interest of farmers.
</P>
<P>
He said among the strategies is to encourage that crops
should be bought at designaed points to facilitate transparency
in the setting up of prices.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kimiti said the Zimbabwean government will continue
supporting the co-operative movement because of its potential in
improving living conditions of millions of people in rural areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
