<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Investment in China's Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- China plans to invest 189 billion
yuan in 1,591 environmental projects over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
This is the largest sum ever allocated for environmental
protection in the country's history, according to a report
in the weekly magazine "Outlook" to be published next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The funds are 30 billion yuan more than the investment in the
three gorges water control project, the largest of its kind in the
world.
</P>
<P>
Environmental protection is of paramount importance and the
only choice for China's economic and social development, the
report quoted Zou Ping, an associate research fellow at the
research office of the State Council, as saying.
</P>
<P>
A report from the State Environmental Protection Bureau says
that the particulate matter in northern Chinese cities averaged
0.392 mg per cubic meter and that of south China, 0.242 mg per
cubic meter, in 1995, far exceeding World Health Organization
limits. Beijing, Shenyang, Xi'an, Shanghai, and Guangzhou were
rated as the most seriously polluted cities in China.
</P>
<P>
Of the total investment, 32.4 billion yuan, or 4 billion US
dollars, will be raised abroad, and China welcomes other
countries' participation in dealing with pollution and foreign
cooperation, technical help, and economic aid, Zou said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment now only makes up 10 percent of China's
total investment in environmental protection. There is a great
potential in attracting foreign funds in this regard, Zou noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0168 </DOCNO>
