<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Top Legislature Passes Three Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- China's President Jiang Zemin today
signed a stringent gun law which strengthens the country's control
on weapons.
</P>
<P>
The President also signed new laws controlling auctions and
archives. They were passed today by China's top legislature, with
decrees signed by Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
The new laws were approved on the closing-day of the 20th
meeting of the National People's Congress Standing Committee,
which was presided by Qiao Shi, chairman of the committee.
</P>
<P>
Consisting of 69 articles in six chapters and integrating
international conventions with practices in China, the Auction Law
regulates the auctioning of goods, auctioneers, auction processes
and legal responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
Agencies engaged in auctions in China will be obliged to abide
by the law from January 1 next year.
</P>
<P>
The Amendments to Archives Law, going into effect today, has
listed criminal responsibilities for people destroying, losing,
illegally providing, faking and reselling archives.
</P>
<P>
The Law on Firearms Control, with 50 articles in eight
chapters, makes regulations on the acquiring of legal firearms by
individuals and organizations, as well as the making, selling,
daily management, transport, and the exit and entry into the
country of guns.
</P>
<P>
The law is aimed at strengthening controls over guns, and
safeguarding public security. Individuals and organizations that
are found to illegally hold, buy or sell, transport, lease and
lend guns will meet severe punishment, according to the general
principles of the law.
</P>
<P>
The law will be put into effect on October 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
Another law on energy saving, which is expected to be passed at
the 20th meeting, was put back on the shelf for further
deliberation, due to the many revisions submitted by members of
the Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
The legislature today also approved the final budget of central
finance in 1995 put forward by the State Council, and a report on
the final budget delivered by Minister of Finance Liu
Zhongli. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Overseas Investment in Guangzhou Economic Development Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Overseas investment in the
Guangzhou Economic and Technological Development Zone in the first
five months of this year, according to recent statistics, reached
1.059 billion U.S. dollars, 47.9 percent over that of the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
An official with the administrative committee of the zone says
that it has attracted more overseas funds by improving its
investment environment and many multinationals have been putting
funds there.
</P>
<P>
Of the new overseas-funded projects in the first three months
this year, 17 of them had 10 million dollars each in investment.
</P>
<P>
Average foreign investment for each of the zone's projects is
about 7.9 million dollars, three times higher than that of China's
other economic development zones.
</P>
<P>
The official attributes the increase mainly to an efficient
administration and more regulations protecting the rights and
interests of overseas investors. Over the past few years, 85
regulations for governing the zone have been adopted.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to other development zones, it usually take an
overseas businessman a mere three to five days here to obtain
approval for a project, and only about 15 minutes to fill out
application forms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maradona could be Barred from Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Argentine football superstar Diego
Maradona could be denied entry into Japan to play in the Japanese
football league because of his drug history, a justice ministry
official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult. Generally speaking, if the conditions of his
entry are the same as before, the result would be the same as
well," said the official of the ministry known for its tough
stance against drug offenders, AFP reported.
</P>
<P>
In May 1994, the World Cup ace was barred from entering Japan
to play friendly matches as Japan's immigration law bans the
entry of those who have been convicted of narcotics charges.
</P>
<P>
Maradona was arrested in Buenos Aires in April 1991 for cocaine
 possession, and five months later was given a 14-month suspended
sentence by an Italian court for the same offence.
</P>
<P>
He was also suspended from international competition for 15
months in 1991 and 1992 after testing positive for cocaine use.
</P>
<P>
Maradona made his comeback in October last year from another
15-month international ban for drug-use, following the 1994 US
World Cup, where he later tested positive for epehedrine.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Maradona said he is ready to leave Argentine first
division club Boca Juniors and play for an unnamed Japanese
team. He has been negotiating a deal that would take him to Japan
until December 1998.
</P>
<P>
The contract could be worth some 20 million dollars, Japanese
media reported.
</P>
<P>
Ricardo Fuika, an agent for Japanese interests, and Maradona's
agent Guillermo Coppola both confirmed Thursday that an agreement
had been reached in principle between the Argentine star and
Japanese clubs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
