<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Government Under Fire over Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Pressure is mounting on the
Indian government to review the price hike in petroleum products
as Janata Dal President Laloo Prasad Yadav and other chief
ministers belonging to the ruling United Front joined the brigade
of critics, the Indian Express said today.
</P>
<P>
The United Front government led by Prime Minister H. D. Deve
Gowda announced on Tuesday a massive price hike in petroleum
products, which became effective on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Many state chief ministers, who began to hold a conference here
Thursday, decided to raise the issue with the prime minister when
they meet him on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The hike seems unreasonable. It should have been done in
phases. I am going to convey the resentment of the people to the
prime minister tomorrow," Laloo Prasad Yadav said at the
conference on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
West Bengal Chief Minister Jyoti Basu, another influential man
of the United Front, said the hike was unjustified. It should
have been effected in installments, he said.
</P>
<P>
While conceding that some amount of price hike may have been
justified, Maharashtra Chief Minister Manohar Joshi believed that
what has been done would cause unbearable burden on the common
man.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Communist Party of India (Marxist) launched a
new round of attacks on the price hike while the Congress Party,
which supports the United Front government from outside, planned
to move a privilege motion against the government in the coming
session of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Facing such mounting pressure, Gowda, who had earlier ruled out
any review, is likely to be forced to eat his own words, analysts
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
