<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment For Yangtze Delta Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (xinhua) -- With China's foreign investment
policy favoring agriculture more and more, foreign investors are
eyeing the agriculture sector in the Yangtze River Delta, a major
grain producer in China.
</P>
<P>
A Beijing-based newspaper reports that companies from some 20
countries and regions have invested in agriculture in the delta,
which covers parts of Zhejiang and Jiangsu provinces, and the
Shanghai Municipality.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, agricultural output of the area, which has good
natural conditions for agricultural development, such as fertile
soil and abundant water resources, was more than 160 billion yuan,
according to "China Import News".
</P>
<P>
Hangjia Lake Plain to the south of the delta, has approved more
than 40 foreign-funded companies in the farming sector, with a
total investment of nearly 100 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Local governments have expressed an interest in foreign
investment, saying that the delta, with its large population and
higher living standard, has a large potential market.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Agriculture, the country has
worked out a series of preferential policies for taxation and use
of land and labor to woo more foreign investment to the sector.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
