<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Children in suffering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will mark the Day of the
African Child on july 30 amid reports of rising poverty and a
host of other problems facing Zimbabwe's children, the Zimbabwe
National News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Minister of National Affairs, Cooperatives
and Employment Creation Thenjiwe Lesabe as saying that today's
children have to contend to with ever-increasing problems the
nation is facing, primary among which, are economic hardships,
resurgence of diseases and disintegration of family structures.
</P>
<P>
''The purpose of observing this day is to advocate for greater
attention, political conviction and resources to africa's
children,'' Lesabe said.
</P>
<P>
Like other countries in Africa, Zimbabwe is faced with a
rapidly increasing population, not matched by infrastructural
development. As a result, the country has a housing crisis dand
sometimes sanitation is compromised as mostly urban authorities
battle to maintain congested sewer system, she added.
</P>
<P>
The Government's welfare arm, the Department of Social Welfare
is recording a steady increase in the number of children needing
assistance.
</P>
<P>
Because of the adverse economic climate, rural children living
around commercial farming areas are forced onto farms to help
sustain households, Lesabe said.
</P>
<P>
The number of children orphaned by the AIDS is estimated to
reach 60,000 by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
One in every 10 people is said to be infected with the
aids-causing hiv virus in Zimbabwe and 300 deaths related to HIV
infection are reported every week.
</P>
<P>
Of all the deaths of children under the age of five, at least
half are caused by HIV/AIDS, according to Health and Child
Welfare Minister Timothy Stamps.
</P>
<P>
''Looking after our children must be the first priority,
because without them to take over tomorrow our economic and
social development programmes would to nil,'' Stamps stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
