<HEADLINE> China's Price Index Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The State Statistics Bureau has
predicted that China's market price index will continuously go up,
but with slower speed this year.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index in the first six months of this year
was up 9.3 percent, and 11.8 percentage points less than the same
period of last year, and the retail price index rose by 7.3
percent during this period, a drop of 11.1 percentage points, the
Shanghai-based "Business News" reported recently.
</P>
<P>
Ren Caifang, head of the Urban Social and Economic Survey Team
under the bureau, said the market price situation in the first
half of this year is better than expected.
</P>
<P>
"This is because of the government's money-tightening policy,
abundant market supply, and the state's regulation of prices for
some goods," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Ren was optimistic about the state control of inflation within
ten percent this year on condition that there is no severe natural
disaster this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
