<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Genes Connected to Intestinal Cancer Discovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Scientists at Zhejiang Medical
University have discovered two genes that they say may provide a
clue to the cause of cancer in the large intestine.
</P>
<P>
The genes, referred to as HSU17714 and HSU20428, were located
from among 46 related genes found in cancer cells in the large
intestine, and were subsequently cloned by the research group,
presided over by Professor Zheng Shu at the university's Tumor
Institute.
</P>
<P>
Cancer of the large intestine is increasing at an annual rate
of 4.2 percent in China and has become the fifth common type of
cancer in the country.
</P>
<P>
Academicians at the Chinese Academy of Sciences say that the
discovery provides a new direction for molecular biological study
of that form of cancer, and is significant for study of the cancer
worldwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
