<HEADLINE> China Doping Control Center Passes IOC Annual Check </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- China Doping Control Center (CDCC)
has passed the annual accreditation test conducted by the
International Olympic Committee recently, the head of CDCC told
Xinhua here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Yang Tianle, a member of the IOC Medical Commission and
Director of CDCC, said he received a congratulatory letter
from Prince Alexandre de Merode, President of the IOC Medical
Commission, on June 21.
</P>
<P>
"In the letter, the President said that CDCC has smoothly
passed the annual accreditation test offered by IOC this year, and
expressed his appreciation of CDCC's timely, reliable and accurate
analyses, " Yang said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, it is the seventh straight time for China to
pass the IOC annual check.
</P>
<P>
Yang said the IOC's demand this year was very tough, requiring
CDCC to clarify eight drugs from six urien samples and completing
the test and research within 72 hours. On May 24, the CDCC sent an
accurate report of 100 pages to IOC.
</P>
<P>
CDCC, an A Class laboratory accredited by the IOC in 1994, owns
26 scientific and technical personnel. Each year about 200 samples
are tested in the laboratory. The samples mainly collected at the
national and international competitions in China as well as those
sent here by other countries.
</P>
<P>
Yang also told Xinhua that China's Olympic Committee has
increased the numbers of flying test from last year. He said Wang
Junxia, world record holder for the women's 10,000 meters, has
received 12 doping checks in the past 12 months. Le Jingyi, world
record holder for the women's 50-meter freestyle swimming, also
received six flying tests and two normal checks conducted by CDCC
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
