<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mergers Change Harbin's Economic Landscape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, July 5 (Xinhua) -- In an effort to revitalize
enterprises in Harbin, an old industrial city of machinery,
textile, medicine, food, automotive, and petrochemical industries
and capital of Heilongjiang Province, 231 money-losing companies
have been merged with 188 productive ones.
</P>
<P>
The Xingguang Machinery Plant, a large state-owned firm in the
northeastern Chinese city had losses of 160 million yuan before it
was merged in 1993 with the First Automotive Works, China's
largest automotive production base, to produce a well managed
plant with better output value and sales.
</P>
<P>
The old planned economy left all state-owned enterprises rigid
in their management, short of capital investment, and out-moded in
technology and equipment, and many were even forced to suspend or
cut production.
</P>
<P>
To reverse this trend, the Chinese government decided, in 1994,
to encourage the city to merge companies for reorganization,
better use of assets, and improved performance. In this way, 300
million yuan worth of assets and 680,000 sq.m. of workspace in the
city were improved and 30,000 employees were given proper jobs.
</P>
<P>
The city's merger system is supposed to be conducted on the
basis of mutual benefits and agreement of both parties and is not
restricted to the city or to the same industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Produce 10 Million Motorcycles This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to produce 10
million motorcycles this year, as against a market demand of 8.5
million units, "China Automotive News" has reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper says that market competition has remained fierce
since the national output of motorcycles topped 7.83 million units
last year.
</P>
<P>
In the past six months domestic motorcycle manufacturers have
been active in increasing production and cutting prices to gain a
larger market share. It has led to large stockpiles, deteriorating
performance and excessive supply.
</P>
<P>
In addition, manufacturers of other products have made a shift
to begin building motorcycles, making market competition even more
intense, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
These new-comers have taken little trouble to push their
products onto the market, since they have enough funds, backing
from governments, flexible marketing strategies and lower
production costs.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) and the 2010
blueprint for the national economy, the motorcycle industry must
make efforts to expand circulation channels, and optimize the
motorcycle market while increasing production scales and standards.
</P>
<P>
China has many large motorcycle and parts trading markets, some
of which are in Guangzhou, Zhuzhou, Jiangmen and Changzhou cities.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
