<HEADLINE> Turkey Criticized for Imposing Secret Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The International Relief Association
(IRA) criticized Turkey for obstructing humanitarian aid reaching
northern Iraq and urged for a policy review under the new government
led by Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Daily News today quoted the relief agencies as saying
that over one million U.S. dollars worth of humanitarian aid in
the form of medicine, provided as part of a campaign organized by
the IRA, faces the prospect of being wasted due to a "secret
embargo" put in place by the Turkish government against northern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The IRA, which is dedicated to alleviating the pain and
suffering of the poor and the needy people around the world, has
brought the six loads of supplies to Turkey, the first arriving
six months ago, for transshipment to northern Iraq, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the first load of supplies is being held at the
Turkish-Iraqi border crossing at Habur. The other five are at the
port of Istanbul with an additional 17 boxes being impounded at
the Istanbul airport since May 9, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
IRA Chairman Khalil Jassemm said:" We tried everything
possible to get the shipments across the border, but we could not
succeed."
</P>
<P>
Negotiations have begun between the IRA and the Turkish Red
Crescent over sending the medicine and medical equipment to
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
IRA officials are trying to do everything to distribute these
supplies before they become spoiled.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the Turkish Foreign Ministry worries that
relief and volunteer organizations working in northern Iraq are
possibly supporting illegal groups or parties in their struggle
against Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
