<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Grow More Grain, Less Cotton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese farmers have grown more
grain and tobacco, but less cotton this year, a survey by the
State Statistics Bureau has found.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted at the end of May, found that China's
rice growing area has ballooned by almost one percent over last
year, to 8.274 million ha this year, while the country's wheat
growing area is 3.9 million hectares, up 4.5 percent over last
year.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, China's cotton growing area has shrunk by
420,000 ha in the past year to 4.2 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the increase of grain growing area has much to
do with the government's decision to raise the grain purchase
price this autumn, while farmers opted to grow less cotton
foreseeing the difficulty of selling cotton.
</P>
<P>
The bearish international cotton market resulted in huge
stockpiles in the Chinese market, dampening textile companies'
enthusiasm in buying cotton from farmers.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that China has grown tobacco over an area of
1.507 ha this year, 17.9 percent more than last year, reflecting a
desire to earn quick money.
</P>
<P>
China produced 465 million tons of grain and 4.5 million tons
of cotton last year, up 4.5 percent and 3.7 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
