<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Two New Nature Reserves Added to International Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Two state nature reserves in China,
the Maolan and Tianmushan, have been accepted as members of
UNESCO's international network of biosphere protection zones.
</P>
<P>
It brings the number of China's nature reserves in the network
to 12.
</P>
<P>
The Maolan nature reserve, located in Libou county in southwest
China's Guizhou Province, is the only surviving karst forest
ecological system protection zone in China, or even in the world's
subtropical areas.
</P>
<P>
It has become a rich "gene bank" of biological resources, and
it also has scenic karst forest tourist resources, providing a
natural laboratory for scientific research and monitoring, and a
scenic spot for ecological tourism.
</P>
<P>
Located in Linan county in east China's Zhejiang Province, the
Tianmushan nature reserve is famous for its unique geographic and
landscapes. It consists of distinctive natural environment,
bountiful biological resources, well-preserved forest ecological
system, and places of historic interest.
</P>
<P>
It boasts a large variety of rare animals and plant species,
including the oldest wild ginkgo trees and cryptomeria groups.
</P>
<P>
Biosphere protection zones attach importance to coordination
between human beings and the natural environment in a global
perspective.
</P>
<P>
The zones lay stress on the combination of their functions,
usually including protection, research, monitoring, education,
training, information communication, and demonstration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
