<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 07:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu, Clinton to Discuss Withdrawal from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu will discuss a U.S.-brokered "Lebanon-first" deal
involving Syria and Israel with President Bill Clinton next week,
a report said today.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is scheduled to visit Washington on July 9 for his
first meeting with Clinton since taking office in June.
</P>
<P>
An official in the Prime Minister's Office was quoted by The
Jerusalem Post as saying that the deal would involve Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon after strict security arrangements
are made.
</P>
<P>
Advisers to President Clinton have discussed this option
recently, but no policy decision has been taken about it, a
senior U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Israel Martin Indyk refused to confirm but
said U.S. would consider the idea until "we have a chance to talk
to the prime minister and see how he wishes to proceed in the
peace process."
</P>
<P>
Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger has called for such
an initiative on south Lebanon this week, terming it a
"land-for-security" arrangement.
</P>
<P>
This echoed a similar plan favored by slain former Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who envisioned the Lebanese Army's
redeployment southward and disarming the Hezbollah. He proposed
that, if this arrangement holds for six to nine months, Israel
would pull out of the security zone.
</P>
<P>
There has been speculation that Netanyahu would support the
same terms to settle the Lebanon question to ensure Israel's
security.
</P>
<P>
However, the major premises of the governments of Rabin and
Shimon Peres were that south Lebanon would be part of a peace
package, whose centerpiece would be an Israeli-Syrian peace treaty
based on Israel's return of the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
As Netanyahu's government has ruled out such a deal with Syria
rejecting any compromise on the Golan Heights, so the central
question remains what incentive would Syria have to agree to the
"Lebanon-first" arrangement.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that Syria apparently wants Israel to stay in
south Lebanon, as this leaves Israel vulnerable to pressure
during the Golan talks. But this approach has failed to cause
Israel to withdraw from the Golan Heights in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
Another official in the Prime Minister's office said the
incentive for Syria should be that if it does not agree to such a
deal, the international community would impose a form of trade
sanctions upon Damascus, due to its support of Hezbollah and
hardline Palestinian and Kurdish groups.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, this official opposed the idea that, in return for
Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon, Syria's control over the
northern half of Lebanon would be formalized.
</P>
<P>
Some sources suggested Israel publicly challenge Syria to make
a deal in south Lebanon or be held responsible for Israel's
indefinite stay on Arab soil, the Post report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Opportunities, Challenges Coexist in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- African countries have also
made progress in regional cooperation which is now on the upswing
in the continent.
</P>
<P>
So far, the east African Inter-Governmental Authority of
Development (IGAD), the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) and the Economic Community of the West African States
(ECOWAS) have worked out projects of regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
However, disequilibrium remains in both Africa's political and
economic areas, and behind the rosy picture still tower many
problems facing the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Although the OAU and the international community have been
making arduous efforts in mediating the internal conflicts in
some African countries, the crises of Burundi, Somalia and
Liberia are far from being resolved.
</P>
<P>
The issues of Somalia, Burundi, Rwanda, Liberia, Sierra Leone
and Angola will still be on the agenda of the forthcoming OAU
summit, waiting for African leaders to find solutions.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, in spite of the economic recovery for three years
running, Africa's economy is still very backward compared with
other continents in the world.
</P>
<P>
Africa is burdened with lack of food and huge debts. By the
end of 1995, debts of African countries reached 322 billion US
Dollars, a four percent increase over that of the previous year.
And the 1995 economic growth rates of 26 African countries were
still below their population increase.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the summit of African leaders will focus on their
economic development and integration for a better Africa. Some
social problems such as refugees which have topped 7 million and
the spreading epidemic AIDS will also be on the agenda for
discussion.
</P>
<P>
All in all, if African states are determined and united to
promote peace and economic development, a better Africa can be
seen not very far away, just as OAU Secretary General Salim A.
Salim put it at the very beginning of this year, "the dream of
the development of Africa is not unreal. Africa can and will
develop." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
