<HEADLINE> Europe Congratulates Yeltsin, Expects Further Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- European leaders today
congratulated Russian President Boris Yeltsin for his victory in
the presidential runoff and hoped that Russia will continue
reforms and cooperate with other European nations.
</P>
<P>
European Union Commission President Jacques Santer and Eastern
European Affairs Commissioner Hans van den Broek said the outcome
of the elections "bodes well for the development of relations
between the European Union and Russia."
</P>
<P>
Javier Solana, secretary general of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), said the alliance is looking forward to
cooperating with the new administration in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating that NATO expects to establish a firm, stable and
lasting "partnership for peace" with Russia, Solana said both NATO
and Russia bear the commitment to safeguard the security and
stability in Europe.
</P>
<P>
In Bonn, Germany, Chancellor Helmut Kohl told reporters that he
had telephoned Yeltsin to congratulate him personally.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Kohl sent a letter to Yeltsin, in which he expressed
confidence that the re-elected president would "proceed undeterred
with the adopted path of comprehensive reforms in Russia and good
cooperation with the international community."
</P>
<P>
From Elysee Palace, France's presidential residence, President
Jacques Chirac said in a message to Yeltsin that he was "very
happy" to work with the latter on developing French-Russian
relationship of "partnership and cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's re-election should serve as a "guarantee of peace and
security in Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Austria and Italy leaders joined other European
countries to hail Yeltsin's victory.
</P>
<P>
Austrian President Thomas Klestil on Thursday sent a message of
congratulations to Yeltsin, and Austrian Prime Minister Franz
Vranitzky said the results of Wednesday's elections meant Russia
could continue to conduct stable international dialogues.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi said that Yeltsin's victory
"inspires growing confidence" in Russia, and Italy's Foreign
Ministry said in a statement that the election result is an
"extremely positive factor" for the stability and security of the
European continent.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin is poised to be the next Russian president after
winning Wednesday's second round of presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
With nearly 54 percent of the vote, he led his Communist rival
Gennady Zyuganov by about 13 percentage points with almost all the
votes counted.
</P>
<P>
The two men entered the run-off after beating eight other
candidates but failing to win more than 50 percent of the votes in
the first round held on June 16. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
