<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The 32nd summit of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) opens in Yaounde, Cameroon
on Monday to discuss its blueprint of peace and development in the
world's poorest continent.
</P>
<P>
The grand gathering of African leaders comes when Africa is
faced with both opportunities and challenges in its political,
economic and social areas.
</P>
<P>
"Africa is not the picture of conflict and disaster that is
portrayed daily by the media," said a joint statement issued by
the chief executives of the OAU, the U.N. Economic Commission for
Africa (ECA) and the African Development Bank recently.
</P>
<P>
Since the 31st OAU summit, political stability in most African
countries has been improved while in some African countries,
internal conflicts and social unrest have been or are being
resolved with the region's "hot spots" being cooled down
gradually in general.
</P>
<P>
The OAU Mechanism for Conflict Prevention, Management and
Resolution, which was set up three years ago, is playing a
greater role in maintaining peace and mediating and resolving
internal conflicts in the region.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, the body's efforts to mediate internal
conflicts in Somalia, Rwanda, Burundi, Liberia, Sierra Leone,
Angola, Sudan and the Comoros have contributed a lot to peace in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the year 1995 saw the fastest economic growth in
Africa since the 1990s. It was also the first time that the
economic growth of 27 African states have surpassed their
population increase, according to the ECA.
</P>
<P>
The ECA predicted that the gross domestic product of African
states will rise by 2.9 percent this year, as against last year's
2.3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
