<HEADLINE> India Plans to Tighten Overseas Investment Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government is
considering measures to tighten the screw on approval of overseas
investment by Indian corporates, the Times of India said today.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials of the Finance Ministry said the approval
given by a special committee of overseas investments of above 4
million US dollars is proposed to be staggered in view of the
emerging balance of payments position as well as the internal
annual ceiling on the total amount of such investments.
</P>
<P>
The special committee comprising officials of the Finance and
Commerce ministries as well as the Reserve Bank of India will also
be required to make an "independent" assessment of the performance
prospects of the overseas investment proposal.
</P>
<P>
This will be a departure from the present practice of the
committee accepting the projections made by applicants on their
face value.
</P>
<P>
The "independent" assessment will, in particular, cover the
likely benefits of an overseas investment proposal in terms of
foreign exchange earning and additional export growth.
</P>
<P>
The new requirements for the approval of overseas investment
are believed to be a reversal of the policy of facilitating
overseas investment by Indian corporates with a view to building
up India's own multinationals.
</P>
<P>
The proposed policy change followed a recent Finance Ministry
review of the working of the present policy which has suggested
that the performance of Indian ventures abroad has often been
unsatisfactory.
</P>
<P>
A large number of ventures have failed to achieve the projected
levels of net foreign exchange earnings or additional exports for
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Becomes Beijing No. 2 Import, Export Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Japan has become Beijing's second
largest import and export partner after the United States,
according to the Beijing Municipal Customs Office.
</P>
<P>
An official at the office said that exports from Beijing to
Japan, and imports from Japan into Beijing, amounted to 433
million US dollars in the first five months of this year, up 13.6
percent over the same period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The official said that exports shot up by 16.3 percent to 135
million dollars, and imports by 12.5 percent to 298 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's trade with Japan during the January-May period was
marked primarily by a substantial increase in the import of
equipment and materials by foreign-funded companies as investment,
he said.
</P>
<P>
During that period, the import of such equipment and materials
surged 76 percent to 58.21 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, exports from foreign-funded companies jumped by 59
percent to 97.84 million dollars, and imports into such companies
by 48.5 percent to 230.7 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
