<HEADLINE> India's Congress Party Leader Moves to Oust Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Indian National Congress
President P.V. Narasimha Rao has decided to crack the whip against
partymen indulging in indiscipline, The Times of India reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The first victim is expected to be one of his main detractors,
former industry minister K. Karunakaran, who is likely to lose the
membership of the Congress Working Committee (CWC) (supreme
decision-making body of the Congress party).
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Rao asked office-bearers of the All India Congress
Committee (AICC) to examine if Karunakaran was a member of the
AICC.
</P>
<P>
Karunakaran has repeatedly criticized Rao and even demanded his
resignation for the unprecedented debacle of the Congress party in
the recent general elections. The senior Congress party leader has
recently speeded up his efforts to solicit support to force the
resignation of Rao as party president.
</P>
<P>
Unlike many other partymen who became members of the AICC after
winning party elections, Karunakaran had become a member by virtue
of being the Congress party's parliamentary leader in the Kerala
state assembly.
</P>
<P>
Now that he is no longer the leader of the Congress legislative
party in Kerala, he has ceased to be an AICC member and also a CWC
member.  
</P>
</TEXT>
