<HEADLINE> Nepali Government Justifies Policy on Telecom Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has
justified its policy to allow private companies into the country's
telecommunication sector, saying that the policy would not harm
the state-run Nepal Telecom Corporation (NTC).
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Communications said Thursday in a press release
that the government was determined to ensure the participation of
the private sector in new telecommunication services like radio
paging and cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
The policy was adopted with a view to making the
telecommunication sector well-organized and spreading the
facilities throughout the country, it said.
</P>
<P>
The NTC would gear ahead competitively if the private sector
was brought into competition while efforts were underway to
provide more autonomy to the corporation, according to the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
However, the government's decision to invite private companies
into the telecom sector has met the opposition from telecom trade
unions in the country.
</P>
<P>
The NTC Workers' Union Thursday undertook a strike for three
hours in a protest against the government's policy of privatizing
the telecommunication services.
</P>
<P>
The strike would continue today across the country, union
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the protest program would be launched next
Monday jointly by the NTC Workers' Union and National Telecom
Employees' Association, they said.
</P>
<P>
They alleged that the government's decision would have an
negative impact on telecommunication customers in remote and rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
Private companies had the only objective of making profit and
would confine their services to urban areas, they said, adding
that competition would lead the state-owned NTC also to withdraw
its services from rural areas.
</P>
<P>
But the government has made clear that it would ask new
telecommunication operators to provide services in remote and
rural areas through necessary regulations and rules.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the government had granted permissions to
nine private companies to operate services like paging and
cellular phone in Nepal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
