<HEADLINE> Demonstrating Teachers Clash With Police in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Sixty-five teachers were arrested
Thursday when they clashed with police during a demonstration here
demanding the reinstatement of sacked teachers, police said.
</P>
<P>
The arrested teachers were released shortly afterwards, the
police said.
</P>
<P>
About 500 teachers from The Nepal National Teachers'
Organization (NNTO) were staging a march on the prime minister's
office demanding a meeting with Prime Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba
when police stopped them with tear gas, according to organization
sources.
</P>
<P>
Over 50 teachers and 10 policemen were injured in the clash,
local reports said.
</P>
<P>
According to Home Minister Khum Bahadur Khadhkla, 65 teachers
were arrested after the nearly three-hour confrontation between
police and the protesters.
</P>
<P>
The NNTO launched a protest program eight months ago urging the
government to satisfy its demands including the reinstatement of
teachers sacked by the present government for political reasons.
</P>
<P>
The NNTO began its latest series of protests including rallies,
sits-in and relay hunger strikes in front of the Ministry of
Education early this week.  
