<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government Not to Sell Rice to Iraq on Credit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has refused to
sell rice to Iraq on credit as the Export-Import Bank of Thailand
will not provide a financial guarantee for the sale.
</P>
<P>
Under a memorandum signed with Iraq in April, the Thai
government was to sell 100,000 tons of 15 percent white rice worth
50 million US dollars to Baghdad on one year's credit, with Iraq
agreeing to buy more rice from Thai private traders.
</P>
<P>
The Export-Import Bank argued that since the United Nations had
allowed Iraq to receive money under the "oil for food" program, it
was inappropriate for Thailand to sell rice to Iraq on credit,
according to Pracha Charutrakulchai, director-general of the
Foreign Trade Department.
</P>
<P>
Pracha said he believed that private traders could replace the
government in supplying the rice.
</P>
<P>
If either side fails to reconfirm the sale, the memorandum will
expire automatically.
</P>
<P>
There are also problems with rice sales to Pyongyang, according
to Commerce Minister Chucheep Harnsawat.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic People's Republic of Korea wants to buy
200,000-300,000 tons of 25 percent white rice from Thailand, but
the buyer still owes Thailand money for previous purchases.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, Thailand exported 2.85 million
tons of rice worth 24.5 billion baht (980 million US dollars).
Exports for the whole year were targeted at 5 million tons worth
45 billion baht (1.8 billion dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
