<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's 30 Reserved Woman MPs Elected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's Election Commission (EC)
has announced the results of the 30 reserved seats for women in
the parliament.
</P>
<P>
In a gazette notification published here today, the EC said
that all the women candidates for the reserved seats were elected
uncontested. 27 of them were from the ruling Awami League (AL) and
the other three went to the Jatiya (National) Party (JP), the
third largest party in the country.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh held its seventh parliament election on June 12 with
the AL becoming the largest party by winning 146 out of 300
parliamentary seats while the ex-ruling Bangladesh Nationalist
Party (BNP) bagged 116 seats, becoming the largest opposition
party and the JP won 32 seats.
</P>
<P>
According to the constitution, there are 30 reserved women
seats to be elected in addition to the 300 seats elected earlier
during the general election.  
</P>
