<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mao Dun Remembered in Hometown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Around 200 people gathered in
Wuzhen, a small town in east China's Zhejiang Province, on
Wednesday to commemorate the 100th anniversary of the birth of Mao
Dun, a great Chinese writer.
</P>
<P>
Mao Dun, born on July 4, 1896, spent his childhood in Wuzhen,
Tongxiang. He organized the Left-Wing Writers League with Lu Xun
in the 1930s, and served as the executive secretary of the league.
</P>
<P>
His representative works include "Midnight", "Spring Silkworms"
and "Store of Lin Family", which vividly recorded social life
in the old China.
</P>
<P>
He died 15 years ago. A stone tablet was erected at the town's
park in commemoration of the writer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
