<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Unveils Deregulation in Fishery Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government Thursday
unveiled a deregulation package on the fishery industry, which
promises less bureaucracy, improved port management and the right
to purchase foreign ships.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Production and Distribution Hartarto,
who announced the reform measures, said "this deregulation is
aimed at improving Indonesia's capability to utilize fishing
potential in a sustainable way which ultimately increases
Indonesia's non-oil and gas exports."
</P>
<P>
The measures would allow selected local companies to buy used
foreign ships and operate them in the 200-nautical-mile exclusive
economic zone (EEZ).
</P>
<P>
Under the reform measures, the minister said, chartered foreign
vessels would not be allowed to operate in Indonesia after the
year 2000. Instead, the Indonesian firms which chartered the ships
would be allowed to buy them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Agriculture Minister Sjarifudin Baharsjah said
Indonesian fishery companies could buy foreign new or used vessels
only when there were no local products and the permit will be
given to the companies with good performance only.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, to achieve a five percent increase
in fishing production or an increase of 160,000 tons of fish per
year, the country needs at least 250 fishing vessels.
</P>
<P>
The government also simplifies the licensing procedures for
operating fishing vessels with both national and foreign flags.
</P>
<P>
Before the deregulation, vessels with national flags have to
obtain 15 documents -- 13 from the Directorate General of Sea and
Transportation, and two from the Directorate General for Fishery.
Under the new deregulation package, the fishery firms only need to
have eight documents to obtain their licenses.
</P>
<P>
Foreign vessels operated by Indonesian fishery firms (vessels
with foreign flags) are now required to have five documents as
compared with six documents before.
</P>
<P>
In order to support the fishery industry, the government also
plans to improve the management of fishery ports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
