<HEADLINE> Solana: NATO to Cooperate with Post-election Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Javier Solana, Secretary General
of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), said today that
the military alliance is looking forward to cooperate with the new
administration in Russia.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on the second round of the Russian presidential
election, which was won by President Boris Yeltsin, Solana called
the outcome of the election as "a further important step towards
consolidation of Russia's reform process."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that NATO wanted a "strong, stable and enduring
partnership" with Russia, stressing that the 16-member
trans-Atlantic alliance and Russia have a common responsibility for
security and stability in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"In Bosnia, NATO and Russian troops are working together to
implement the Peace Agreement," he noted. "This shows that we can
cooperate effectively on issues of European peace and stability."
</P>
<P>
He stated that NATO was determined to build upon this
experience and hoped the two sides would soon be able to make
further progress.
</P>
<P>
"I am looking forward to cooperating with the Russian President
and new Russian government in developing the strong framework we
want to give to our partnership," Solana said. 
</P>
