<HEADLINE> Dalian officials Urged to Learn Foreign Languages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Every official and civil servant
under the age of 50 in Dalian City in Northeast China's Liaoning
Province have been told to learn a foreign language.
</P>
<P>
They have to study English or Japanese languages training in
their spare time.
</P>
<P>
According to an order issued by Dalian municipal party
committee and government, the people have to take examinations
after the language training mainly through special television and
radio programs.
</P>
<P>
The order stipulates that the city's appointment of new
officials will take into consideration the foreign language level
of job candidates.
</P>
<P>
In a recent public invitation for the recruitment of 15
officials at bureau level in Dalian City, foreign language was an
exam item.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, employees in commercial, tourism and
communications departments are also required to receive foreign
language training.
</P>
<P>
The city also decided to take three to five years to popularize
foreign language study among all its citizens.
</P>
<P>
Dalian is one of China's first group of coastal cities that
implemented an opening to the outside world policy. It takes the
lead in introducing foreign investment in Northeast China's three
provinces.
</P>
<P>
However, the lack of personnel who have mastered foreign
languages has hindered the city's development. City authorities
called on officials and citizens to learn foreign languages in an
effort to make the city open more widely to the outside world, and
to help build Dalian into an international city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
