<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Workers Face the Sack In Japan War Software Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tianjin, July 5 (Xinhua) Four Chinese workers at a
Japanese-funded firm in north China port city Tianjin face being
fired after refusing to develop computer game software featuring
war battles between Japan and allied troops during World War II.
</P>
<P>
The four young Chinese men claim the software, "Final Decision
of the Governor", would hurt the feelings of Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
The software, a product of Japanese Tianjin Koei Company,
features a battle between the troops of Japanese, Chinese and the
United States during the Second World War in the Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Guo Haijing, one of the four workers, in an interview with
Xinhua, said they knew they could lose their jobs for their
refusal.
</P>
<P>
"We would not give in since national dignity is more
important," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is unacceptable for us to make with our own hands the
images of the former Japanese troops", he added.
</P>
<P>
The four people were hired by the Japanese firm last year to
develop computer graphs after their graduation from a local arts
institute. They were asked on May 13 to develop cartoon pictures
for the software using material provided by the Japanese company.
</P>
<P>
Liang Guangming, a 24 year-old employee, said the material
contained Japanese warplanes and warships used during the war, and
images of Japanese officers, including the name of chief war
criminal Hideki Tojo.
</P>
<P>
Hideki was sentenced to death by the Far East military tribunal
soon after the war, as one of chief culprits of the Japanese War
of Aggression against China (1937-1945).
</P>
<P>
About 35 million Chinese people were killed or wounded during
the war, and the economic losses for China reached 560 billion US
dollars, according to an official document compiled in China in
the late 1940s.
</P>
<P>
"The war criminals, who were responsible for the death of many
Chinese people, were generals in the software program, which is
unacceptable to us," Liang said.
</P>
<P>
"What embarrassed us most was the scene of hailing Japanese
troops after they won a battle," he said.
</P>
<P>
Liang and his three colleagues were threatened by the Japanese
manager of the company with dismissal immediately after they
refused to develop the software.
</P>
<P>
The company also set up a branch in Beijing, which takes
advantage of China's rich resources of software developers to
produce graphs of basic images, and Chinese versions of software.
</P>
<P>
Their products are exported to Southeast Asia, Hong Kong and
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The games software "Final Decision of the Governor", is said to
have offended some people in Shanghai when it entered the city
last year.
</P>
<P>
Three college students demanded an investigation into the
import of the software in a letter to local government.
</P>
<P>
An investigation by local experts say the software is
misleading, and advocates militarism. They have demanded the
recall of the 'offending' software.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Government Formed in Czech Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Czech President Vaclav Havel today
reappointed Vaclav Klaus as prime minister of a new three-party
coalition government, one month after Klaus lost his parliamentary
majority in the legislative elections.
</P>
<P>
This is also the first government of the independent Czech
Republic, which divided from the former Czech and Slovak
Federation in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member cabinet, formed after two weeks' long and
difficult negotiations, includes seven members from Klaus' Civic
Democratic Party (CDP), and four each from his two small partners
in the center-right coalition, the Christian Democratic
Union-Czechoslovak People's Party and the the Civic Democratic
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
The CDP occupied most of the key posts including those of
foreign minister, interior minister and finance minister.
</P>
<P>
In last month's parliamentary elections, the ruling coalition
won 99 seats in the 200-member parliament, narrowly losing its
majority.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that facing the challenges from both the
majority opposition and the coalition itself, Klaus' government
will have a tough time during its coming four-year term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
