<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will repatriate all of the
4,000 Vietnamese refugees in a northwest province within the next
three months, a Thai security official said.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese refugees in Sikhiu district, Nakhon Ratchasima,
will be sent back to Vietnam in two batches within three months,
according to Thai National Security Council Deputy Chief
Khachadpai Burusapatana.
</P>
<P>
Thailand began repatriating Vietnamese refugees in Sikhiu camp
on June 29, one day before funding from relevant United Nations
agencies stopped.
</P>
<P>
A total of 87 Vietnamese refugees, including some of the 127
hard-core leaders who refused to return to Vietnam, were
repatriated in the first batch.
</P>
<P>
During the first repatriation action, some of the hard-core
leaders injured themselves to protest against forced repatriation.
</P>
