<HEADLINE> EU Provides New Humanitarian Aid Package to Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) decided
today to provide a new package of humanitarian aid worth 13.075
million ECUs (about 17 million U.S. dollars) for Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Approved by the European Commission (EC), the 15-nation
alliance's executive arm, the aid will be channeled through the
European Community Humanitarian Office (ECHO).
</P>
<P>
The ECHO has been providing funds for medical and food aid, and
water supply projects southern Sudan in response to the pressing
needs of civilians caught in the ongoing conflict.
</P>
<P>
Part of the new aid will support operations in and around
Khartoum, where about 1.9 million people who have left their homes
elsewhere in Sudan are living in very poor conditions.
</P>
<P>
The package will also support some 200,000 Sudanese refugees
now living in camps in northern Uganda, and finance ECHO flight to
ferry goods and passengers for humanitarian organizations.
</P>
<P>
The latest aid package brings the ECHO funding for victims of
armed conflict in Sudan since 1994 to a total of 61 million ECUs
(about 80 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
