<HEADLINE> Another Italian Judge Arrested in Graft Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Another prominent Italian magistrate
was arrested today along with three lawyers and an accountant, as
a result of a widening graft probe into Rome's judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Local news reports said magistrate Antonio Pelaggi was accused
of being paid 400 million lire (about 265,000 U.S. dollars) by a
construction businessman in exchange of acquitting him from a tax
fraud case.
</P>
<P>
The event took place in the late 1980s and early 1990s. The
businessman involved, Renato Armellini, died in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Investigators said the arrests were ordered on the basis of the
information from Armellini's son-in-law, who told prosecutors the
builder had taken a bag filled with money with him to meet judge
Pelaggi.
</P>
<P>
A series of court scandals broke open in March, when top Rome
judge Renato Squillante, 71, was arrested in an unrelated
corruption case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru's Infant Mortality Rate Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The mortality rate of children less
than a year old dropped noticeably in Peru, and so did the
fertility rate, according to the National Institute of Statistics
and Informatics.
</P>
<P>
A demographic and family health survey showed that 73 of every
1,000 children born alive died before reaching the age of one year
in 1986. The rate dropped to 55 in 1991 and is expected to go down
further to 40 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The survey also indicated that Peruvian women's fertility rate
dropped from 4.1 children in 1986 to 3.5 in 1991, but only 2.5
children were wanted.
</P>
<P>
The country will hold its third demographic and family health
survey from August to November this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
