<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Analyzes Malnutrition in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A meeting of the United
Nations Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) opened in
Asuncion, Paraguay, today to analyze the situation of malnutrition
in Latin America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will study measures to improve the situation which
affects 43 percent of the population in the region.
</P>
<P>
FAO Director-General Jacques Diouf said about 59 million people
in the region are suffering from chronic malnutrition and other 64
million are threatened by the problem.
</P>
<P>
Poverty affects 53 percent of the population in rural areas
while 34 percent in urban areas, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the FAO, the region's 800 million people do not
have enough food and more than 200 million children under 5 suffer
protein and calories insufficiency.
</P>
<P>
Diouf called for solutions to the future problems of the
world's population, which will grow to 8,700 million in the next
35 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
