<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Landscapes Built At Great Wall End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, July 5 (Xinhua) -- New man-made scenery featuring
the accomplishments of a famous general from the Ming Dynasty
(1368-1644) has been built at the eastern end of the Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
Laolongtou, or "old dragon head," was a strategic military
point surrounded by mountains and the sea. Qi Jiguang, the famous
general who fought Japanese pirates, built a stone wall into the
sea here and trained his navy nearby.
</P>
<P>
A stone bust of General Qi, replicas of warships, soldiers
scaling ladders, and various weapons used by Qi's troops were
added to the Laolongtou scenic zone.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of this year, nearly 117,000 domestic
and overseas tourists visited the scenic zone, on the coast of
Bohai Bay in north China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
