<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thirty-two Nowly Born David's Deers in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Tian Ezhou Nature Preservation
Region in central China's Hubei province recently had 32 newborn
baby David's deers.
</P>
<P>
The number of the David's deers has reached 111 in the nature
reserve, which has successfully raised the rare animals in a
complete natural environment.
</P>
<P>
The David's deers, known as "Milu" or "Sibuxiang" in China,
were raised in the imperial hunting gardens in ancient times.
</P>
<P>
The rare animal died out in the wild in China, its native home,
around the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
However, some had been taken to European in the latter of the
19th century by a Catholic priest and naturalist Pere David. Hence
the name David's deer.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, some 30 of the rare species returned home to China as
gifts by Britain, which now are raised in the 1,500-hectare Tian
Ezhou preserve, a "happy paradize" rich in woods, grassland, red
marshes and lakes.
</P>
<P>
A survey showed that about 2,000 head of the deer are now in
the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
