<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Border Area Popular Among Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Lush scenery and local culture have
attracted a growing number of tourists to the Xishuangbanna Dai
Autonomous Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
According to local statistics, 1.54 million tourists visited
the prefecture in 1995, at the Sino-Myanmar borders in southwest
China's Yunnan Province. Of those visitors, 23,600 were from
abroad.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, the number of domestic and overseas
visitors has grown yearly at an average rate of 27.7 percent and
20 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the local tourism industry brought in
7.3 million US dollars in foreign exchange, with an annual average
growth of 116.9 percent, and contributed 950 million yuan to local
revenues.
</P>
<P>
Located on the chief water and land traffic passage connecting
southeast Asia and southwest China, Xishuangbanna is an ideal
tourist destination with its beautiful tropical scenery and unique
folk customs, said a tourism official with the prefecture
government.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that the government has invested heavily in
infrastructure in the past five years, which has promoted the
local tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 1995, the prefecture renovated the Jinghong
Airport and the Daluo highway, and installed 25,600 program
controlled telephones and 480 lines for paging and mobile phone
services.
</P>
<P>
Several hotels, entertainment businesses, and parks featuring
Xishuangbanna's ethnic culture were also built.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that 80,000 overseas travelers and three
million domestic sightseers will visit Xishuangbanna by the year
2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960705.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defending Champion Sampras Crashes out of Wimbledon Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WIMBLEDON, ENGLAND, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Pete
Sampras of the United States and fourth-seeded Goran Ivanisevic of
Croatia have both been knocked out by unseeded players in the
quarter-finals clashes at the Wimbledon Tennis Championships here
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During the frustrating match, suspended frequently by rain,
world number one Sampras, who has won three consecutive Wimbledon
titles over the past three years, seemed unable to cope with his
bigger Dutch opponent Richard Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
The tall and strong Dutch player, who just forced 1991
Wimbledon men's single champion Michael Stich out of the
tournament, was in superb attacking form and gave Sampras simply
no chance to launch effective counterattacks.
</P>
<P>
Krajicek, who hit about 30 aces in the match, snatched the
victory over the title holder in straight sets, 7-5, 7-6, 6-4 and
sailed into the men's semi-finals. The Dutch player is very much
likel to the hottest candidate to win the Wimbledon men's singles
trophy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the match, Krajick said he would not be able to
toast his two-day win over top seed Sampras, "the tournament is
not finished yet and there's no time to celeberate because I've
not even got a day off since Friday."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sampras said: "Richard goav me my toughest test ever
out here and I was'nt good enough. He returned and passed me
better than I thought he could and he thoroughly deserved to win."
</P>
<P>
The American tennis ace noted that he had to focus his
attention on the U.S. Open after this crucial defeat, "I'll have
to put this result into perspective and bounce back with good
display there," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ivanisevic, bidding to reach his fifth Wimbledon semi-final,
lost a long and difficult battle against unseeded Austrilian Jason
Stoltenberg 3-6, 6-7, 7-6, 6-7. The latter obtained a berth in
the semi-finals, in which he is due to clash with Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
In another two men's singles quarter-final clashes, two
American players the 13th-seeded Todd Martin and unseeded MaliVai
Washingtonof defeated British player Tim Henman and Alex Radusecu
of Germany and joined hands into the semi-finals, but
unfortunately the two Amercians would have an in-fighting in the
semi-finals in a bid to reach the men's singles final.
</P>
<P>
In the women's singles semi-final matches, the fourth-seeded
Arantxa Sanchez Vicario of Spain thrashed his American opponent
Meredith McGrath in straight sets 6-2, 6-1 in only one hour and
gained a place in the women's singles final for the second year
running.
</P>
<P>
But in the other semi-final match between defending champion
Stetti Graf of Germany and Japanese player Kimiko Date, the world
number one Graf snatched the first set 6-2 quite easily.
</P>
<P>
In the second set, the 12th-seed Date, who is always a
slow-starter, launched really powerful attacks upon the defending
champion and took the set by the same 6-2.
</P>
<P>
When Date seemed very much likely to create the biggest upset
by ousting Graf, the match, which started very late due to the
frequent rain interruptions of previous matches, was suspended and
would be re-started tomorrow morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
