<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves 3 Credits for African Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has okayed three
credits totaling 135 million U.S. dollars for development projects
in Mali, Cote D'Ivoire and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Bank's recent announcement, a credit of
about 60 million dollars equivalent is provided for a Mali
economic management project. The project will support the
government's efforts to deepen fiscal adjustment and provide a
stable macroeconomic environment that is conducive to sustained
private sector-led economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Another credit of about 40 million dollars equivalent is
approved for Cote D'Ivoire's integrated health services
development project. The project is designed to expand access to
health services and improve their utilization, make services
available on a sustainable basis, and improve the ability of the
Ministry of Public Health to analyze health problems.
</P>
<P>
The third credit of some 35 million dollars will be provided to
another Western African country, Sierra Leone. The funding for its
transport sector project will help the implementation of a new
sector policy and strategy. It will finance capacity building to
expand institutional reform and strengthening, and increase the
use of labor-intensive methods in road works and road maintenance.
</P>
<P>
The credits will be channeled through the International
Development Association, the concessionary lending wing of the
World Bank for developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
