<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manchester to Get 21m Pounds to Rebuild Its City Centre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The British government is
redistributing regional aid funds to give Manchester an extra 21
million pounds (33 million US dollars) to help rebuild its city
centre following last month's IRA bombing, the Financial Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
About 20 million pounds (31 million US dollars) will come from
reallocating some of the two billion pounds (3.1 billion US
dollars) in European Union (EU) regional aid for 1997-99, using
money originally designated for other parts of the UK.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Trade and Industry denied that redistributing
the two billion pounds regional aid fund in Manchester's favour
would have much effect on other parts of the UK. "It's 0.5 percent
of the budget. It's not a big deal," said an official.
</P>
<P>
The government will provide a further one million pounds (1.55
million US dollars) to pay for a master plan to redevelop the
damaged city centre, and another 150,000 pounds (232,500 US
dollars) to support an international urban design competition that
will provide the blueprint for the work.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the package, Michael Heseltine, the Deputy Prime
Minister, said the goal should be to "redesign the city centre for
the 21st century", and he hoped that the world's best architects
and urban planners would take part. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
