<HEADLINE> Plavsic Says to Have Taken Over Full Power from Karadzic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July (Xinhua) -- Acting President of Bosnian Serb
state Biljana Plavsic said here today that she has taken over all
presidential powers in the Serb entity Republika Srpska since June
30.
</P>
<P>
Prior to that, there was a brief vacuum, Plavsic told reporters
after meeting with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian Serb President Radovan Karadzic transferred power to
his deputy Plavsic on Sunday under intensive international
pressure. International community has threatened to reimpose
sanctions against Bosnian Serbs unless Karadzic, who was indicted
as war criminal by the international war crimes tribunal, stepped
down. Karadzic also said Wednesday he would not run for the
upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
Plavisc, also a hardliner, said intensive efforts were under
way for the implementation of the Dayton accords.
</P>
<P>
"We are now trying to include all institutions and all
Republika Srpska departments so as to make up for the lost time
and to have the Dayton accords implemented in the envisaged
order," Plavsic said.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting with Milosevic, Plavsic offered strong
assurances that the Serb entity would continue successfully to
implement the Dayton peace accords, according to Tanjug news
agency.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic stressed the significance of all-round cooperation of
the Republika Srpska leadership with the international community
which is engaged in the successful implementation of the peace
plan, especially in preparations for the September 14 elections.
</P>
<P>
It was in the greatest interest of Bosnian Serb citizens to
have democratically and legally elected institutions, which would
no doubt help reaffirm the Bosnian serb entity, the Serbian
president said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
