<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cost of Living in Britain the Lowest in EU: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The cost of living in Britain is the
lowest in the 15-nation European Union (EU), according to a survey
published today.
</P>
<P>
Britain is put by ECA International, a global network of nearly
800 multinational member companies which track the cost of more
than 200 goods and services, at the bottom of its Cost of Living
League of EU countries.
</P>
<P>
Within the EU, Denmark keeps its place as the most expensive
country, with goods and services 71 percent more costly than
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Among 28 European countries surveyed, Britain this year comes
24th, beaten for cheapness only by Hungary, Poland, Turkey and the
Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland emerges as the most expensive country in Europe and
is number three out of 108 countries surveyed across the world. It
is 87 percent more costly than Britain, which is placed 61st in
the world, two places lower than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Japan is the most expensive country in the world, as it has
been for more than five years. It is now reckoned to be 134
percent more expensive than Britain.
</P>
<P>
Barry Rodin, a senior ECA consultant, said: "The cost of living
in Britain has been cheaper than other countries in the EU since
Britain left the exchange-rate mechanism in 1992."
</P>
<P>
"It would be expected that European unity would have led to a
convergence in the cost of living but these figures show this
hasn't happened. There is still a significant gulf between
countries like Denmark and Germany at the top and Portugal and the
UK at the bottom," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
