<HEADLINE> Former Elf President Accused of Abusing Social Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Loik Le Floch Prigent, president of
the National Railway Company of France (SNCF) and former president
of the Elf-Aquitaine oil group, today was accused of abusing
social funds by a local court here.
</P>
<P>
Judge Eva Joly told the 52-year-old SNCF president that she is
also considering to have him put in jailed.
</P>
<P>
Prigent, who was president of Elf-Aquitaine oil company from
May 1989 to August 1993, was also accused of "hiding the action
of abusing social funds, abusing of trust, hiding the action of
abusing trust, spreading false information and presenting false
documents."
</P>
<P>
Elf-Aquitaine gulped down 800 million francs (153 million U.S.
dollars) in the process of saving the textile group Bidermann in
early 1990's, and this raised doubt over possible financial abuse
by the leaders of the group.
</P>
<P>
Two French watch-dog institutions, the Commission of Stock
Exchange Operations and the Court of Accounts, submitted two
reports expressing doubt over the case, and the Paris Attorney
General, or le Paquet de Paris, launched an inquiry into the
affair in August 1994.
</P>
<P>
The inquiry led to the detention of the head of the Bildermann
group, Maurice Bidermann on May 24, and the judicial investigation
of six other persons, including the ex-wife of Prigent, Fatima
Belaid, who was suspected of having benefited from the
"generosity of Maurice Bidermann". She was accused of "covering
the action of abusing social properties".
</P>
<P>
Prigent has claimed his innocence in the case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
