<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zaire Threatens to Evict Rwandan Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Zaire has threatened the use of
force against the 1.5 million Rwandan refugees on its territory
and made an urgent call to the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) on their prompt repatriation.
</P>
<P>
"It is not that we are driving them out. We are obliged to do
that unless there is a prompt repatriation, because our national
security is severely threatened by them," declared Zairian Deputy
Premier Kititua Ntuoiansi at the end of the OAU Council of
Ministers meeting tonight.
</P>
<P>
"Our police are paralyzed before the Rwandan refugees who are
often armed. That's why we have to use the military," said
Ntuoiansi who is in charge of Zaire's foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said the Rwandan delegation has made an "urgent call" to
the council of ministers meeting which began this morning.
</P>
<P>
Senior Zairian officials said here today that the Council of
Ministers meeting is set to pass a resolution on the Rwandan
refugees which the Zairian government hopes will include stepping
up the repatriation process.
</P>
<P>
Zaire, with its largest share of refugee burden in Africa, now
hosts 1.6 million African refugees on its territory, including
over one million Rwandans, mostly the majority Hutus who fled for
fear of revenge for the 1994 ethnic killings at home.
</P>
<P>
Reports say the Rwandan refugees are now forming an army with
trafficked arms, causing instability to both Zaire and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"It is simply beyond our capacity to manage them any more,"
said Ntuoiansi in an interview with Xinhua earlier today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
